# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jet-propulsion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:jet-propulsion/aircraft-propulsion] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The first line of defence consists in avoiding detection, through mechanisms such as camouflage, masquerade, apostatic selection, living underground, or nocturnality.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Members of groups are at reduced risk of predation, despite the increased conspicuousness of a group, through improved vigilance, predator confusion, and the likelihood that the predator will attack some other individual.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Animals may avoid becoming prey by living out of sight of predators, whether in caves, burrows, or by being nocturnal.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Nocturnality is an animal behavior characterized by activity during the night and sleeping during the day.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This is a behavioral form of detection avoidance called crypsis used by animals to either avoid predation or to enhance prey hunting.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Predation risk has long been recognized as critical in shaping behavioral decisions.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, this predation risk is of prime importance in determining the time of evening emergence in echolocating bats.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Although early access during brighter times permits easier foraging, it also leads to a higher predation risk from bat hawks and bat falcons.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This results in an optimum evening emergence time that is a compromise between the conflicting demands.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Another nocturnal adaptation can be seen in kangaroo rats.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] They forage in relatively open habitats, and reduce their activity outside their nest burrows in response to moonlight.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] During a full moon, they shift their activity towards areas of relatively dense cover to compensate for the extra brightness.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Camouflage uses any combination of materials, coloration, or illumination for concealment to make the organism hard to detect by sight.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] It is common in both terrestrial and marine animals.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Camouflage can be achieved in many different ways, such as through resemblance to surroundings, disruptive coloration, shadow elimination by countershading or counter-illumination, self-decoration, cryptic behavior, or changeable skin patterns and colour.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Animals such as the flat-tail horned lizard of North America have evolved to eliminate their shadow and blend in with the ground.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The bodies of these lizards are flattened, and their sides thin towards the edge.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This body form, along with the white scales fringed along their sides, allows the lizards to effectively hide their shadows.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In addition, these lizards hide any remaining shadows by pressing their bodies to the ground.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Animals can hide in plain sight by masquerading as inedible objects.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, the potoo, a South American bird, habitually perches on a tree, convincingly resembling a broken stump of a branch, while a butterfly, *Kallima*, looks just like a dead leaf.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Another way to remain unattacked in plain sight is to look different from other members of the same species.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Predators such as tits selectively hunt for abundant types of insect, ignoring less common types that were present, forming search images of the desired prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This creates a mechanism for negative frequency-dependent selection, apostatic selection.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Many species make use of behavioral strategies to deter predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In the absence of toxins or other defences, this is essentially bluffing, in contrast to aposematism which involves honest signals.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Pursuit-deterrent signals are behavioral signals used by prey to convince predators not to pursue them.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, gazelles stot, jumping high with stiff legs and an arched back.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This is thought to signal to predators that they have a high level of fitness and can outrun the predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] As a result, predators may choose to pursue a different prey that is less likely to outrun them.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] White-tailed deer and other prey mammals flag with conspicuous (often black and white) tail markings when alarmed, informing the predator that it has been detected.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Warning calls given by birds such as the Eurasian jay are similarly honest signals, benefiting both predator and prey: the predator is informed that it has been detected and might as well save time and energy by giving up the chase, while the prey is protected from attack.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Another pursuit-deterrent signal is thanatosis or playing dead.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Thanatosis is a form of bluff in which an animal mimics its own dead body, feigning death to avoid being attacked by predators seeking live prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Thanatosis can also be used by the predator in order to lure prey into approaching.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] An example of this is seen in white-tailed deer fawns, which experience a drop in heart rate in response to approaching predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This response, referred to as "alarm bradycardia", causes the fawn's heart rate to drop from 155 to 38 beats per minute within one beat of the heart.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This drop in heart rate can last up to two minutes, causing the fawn to experience a depressed breathing rate and decrease in movement, called tonic immobility.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Tonic immobility is a reflex response that causes the fawn to enter a low body position that simulates the position of a corpse.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Upon discovery of the fawn, the predator loses interest in the "dead" prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Other symptoms of alarm bradycardia, such as salivation, urination, and defecation, can also cause the predator to lose interest.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Marine molluscs such as sea hares, cuttlefish, squid and octopuses give themselves a last chance to escape by distracting their attackers.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] To do this, they eject a mixture of chemicals, which may mimic food or otherwise confuse predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In response to a predator, animals in these groups release ink, creating a cloud, and opaline, affecting the predator's feeding senses, causing it to attack the cloud.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Distraction displays attract the attention of predators away from an object, typically the nest or young, that is being protected, as when some birds feign a broken wing while hopping about on the ground.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Mimicry occurs when an organism (the mimic) simulates signal properties of another organism (the model) to confuse a third organism.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This results in the mimic gaining protection, food, and mating advantages.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] There are two classical types of defensive mimicry: Batesian and Müllerian.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Both involve aposematic coloration, or warning signals, to avoid being attacked by a predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In Batesian mimicry, a palatable, harmless prey species mimics the appearance of another species that is noxious to predators, thus reducing the mimic's risk of attack.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This form of mimicry is seen in many insects.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The idea behind Batesian mimicry is that predators that have tried to eat the unpalatable species learn to associate its colors and markings with an unpleasant taste.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This results in the predator learning to avoid species displaying similar colours and markings, including Batesian mimics, which are in effect parasitic on the chemical or other defences of the unprofitable models.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Some species of octopus can mimic a selection of other animals by changing their skin color, skin pattern and body motion.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] When a damselfish attacks an octopus, the octopus mimics a banded sea snake.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The model chosen varies with the octopus's predator and habitat.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Most of these octopuses use Batesian mimicry, selecting an organism repulsive to predators as a model.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In Müllerian mimicry, two or more aposematic forms share the same warning signals, as in viceroy and monarch butterflies.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Birds avoid eating both species because their wing patterns honestly signal their unpleasant taste.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Many animals are protected against predators with armour in the form of hard shells (such as most molluscs and turtles), leathery or scaly skin (as in reptiles), or tough chitinous exoskeletons (as in arthropods).
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A spine is a sharp, needle-like structure used to inflict pain on predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] An example of this seen in nature is in the sohal surgeonfish.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] These fish have a sharp scalpel-like spine on the front of each of their tail fins, able to inflict deep wounds.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The area around the spines is often brightly colored to advertise the defensive capability; predators often avoid the Sohal surgeonfish.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Defensive spines may be detachable, barbed or poisonous.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Porcupine spines are long, stiff, break at the tip, and in some species are barbed to stick into a would-be predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In contrast, the hedgehog's short spines, which are modified hairs, readily bend, and are barbed into the body, so they are not easily lost; they may be jabbed at an attacker.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Many species of slug caterpillar, Limacodidae, have numerous protuberances and stinging spines along their dorsal surfaces.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Species that possess these stinging spines suffer less predation than larvae that lack them, and a predator, the paper wasp, chooses larvae without spines when given a choice.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Group living can decrease the risk of predation to the individual in a variety of ways, as described below.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A dilution effect is seen when animals living in a group "dilute" their risk of attack, each individual being just one of many in the group.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Hamilton proposed that group living evolved because it provides benefits to the individual rather than to the group as a whole, which becomes more conspicuous as it becomes larger.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] One common example is the shoaling of fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Experiments provide direct evidence for the decrease in individual attack rate seen with group living, for example in Camargue horses in Southern France.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The horse-fly often attacks these horses, sucking blood and carrying diseases.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] When the flies are most numerous, the horses gather in large groups, and individuals are indeed attacked less frequently.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Water striders are insects that live on the surface of fresh water, and are attacked from beneath by predatory fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Experiments varying the group size of the water striders showed that the attack rate per individual water strider decreases as group size increases.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The selfish herd theory was proposed by W.D.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Hamilton to explain why animals seek central positions in a group.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The theory's central idea is to reduce the individual's domain of danger.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A domain of danger is the area within the group in which the individual is more likely to be attacked by a predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The center of the group has the lowest domain of danger, so animals are predicted to strive constantly to gain this position.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Testing Hamilton's selfish herd effect, Alta De Vos and Justin O'Rainn (2010) studied brown fur seal predation from great white sharks.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Using decoy seals, the researchers varied the distance between the decoys to produce different domains of danger.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The seals with a greater domain of danger had an increased risk of shark attack.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A radical strategy for avoiding predators which may otherwise kill a large majority of the emerging stage of a population is to emerge very rarely, at irregular intervals.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Predators with a life-cycle of one or a few years are unable to reproduce rapidly enough in response to such an emergence.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Predators may feast on the emerging population, but are unable to consume more than a fraction of the brief surfeit of prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Periodical cicadas, which emerge at intervals of 13 or 17 years, are often used as an example of this predator satiation, though other explanations of their unusual life-cycle have been proposed.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Animals that live in groups often give alarm calls that give warning of an attack.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, vervet monkeys give different calls depending on the nature of the attack: for an eagle, a disyllabic cough; for a leopard or other cat, a loud bark; for a python or other snake, a "chutter".
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Similar calls are found in other species of monkey, while birds also give different calls that elicit different responses.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In the improved vigilance effect, groups are able to detect predators sooner than solitary individuals.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For many predators, success depends on surprise.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] If the prey is alerted early in an attack, they have an improved chance of escape.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, wood pigeon flocks are preyed upon by goshawks.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Goshawks are less successful when attacking larger flocks of wood pigeons than they are when attacking smaller flocks.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This is because the larger the flock size, the more likely it is that one bird will notice the hawk sooner and fly away.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Once one pigeon flies off in alarm, the rest of the pigeons follow.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Wild ostriches in Tsavo National Park in Kenya feed either alone or in groups of up to four birds.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] As the ostrich group size increases, the frequency at which each individual raises its head to look for predators decreases.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Because ostriches are able to run at speeds that exceed those of lions for great distances, lions try to attack an ostrich when its head is down.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] By grouping, the ostriches present the lions with greater difficulty in determining how long the ostriches' heads stay down.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Thus, although individual vigilance decreases, the overall vigilance of the group increases.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Individuals living in large groups may be safer from attack because the predator may be confused by the large group size.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] As the group moves, the predator has greater difficulty targeting an individual prey animal.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The zebra has been suggested by the zoologist Martin Stevens and his colleagues as an example of this.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] When stationary, a single zebra stands out because of its large size.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] To reduce the risk of attack, zebras often travel in herds.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The striped patterns of all the zebras in the herd may confuse the predator, making it harder for the predator to focus in on an individual zebra.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Furthermore, when moving rapidly, the zebra stripes create a confusing, flickering motion dazzle effect in the eye of the predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Defensive structures such as spines may be used both to ward off attack as already mentioned, and if need be to fight back against a predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Methods of fighting back include chemical defences, mobbing, defensive regurgitation, and suicidal altruism.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Many prey animals, and to defend against seed predation also seeds of plants, make use of poisonous chemicals for self-defence.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] These may be concentrated in surface structures such as spines or glands, giving an attacker a taste of the chemicals before it actually bites or swallows the prey animal: many toxins are bitter-tasting.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A last-ditch defence is for the animal's flesh itself to be toxic, as in the puffer fish, danaid butterflies and burnet moths.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Many insects acquire toxins from their food plants; *Danaus* caterpillars accumulate toxic cardenolides from milkweeds (Asclepiadaceae).
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Some prey animals are able to eject noxious materials to deter predators actively.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The bombardier beetle has specialized glands on the tip of its abdomen that allows it to direct a toxic spray towards predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The spray is generated explosively through oxidation of hydroquinones and is sprayed at a temperature of 100 °C.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Armoured crickets similarly release blood at their joints when threatened (autohaemorrhaging).
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Several species of grasshopper including *Poecilocerus pictus*, *Parasanaa donovani*, *Aularches miliaris*, and *Tegra novaehollandiae* secrete noxious liquids when threatened, sometimes ejecting these forcefully.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Spitting cobras accurately squirt venom from their fangs at the eyes of potential predators, striking their target eight times out of ten, and causing severe pain.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Termite soldiers in the Nasutitermitinae have a fontanellar gun, a gland on the front of their head which can secrete and shoot an accurate jet of resinous terpenes "many centimeters".
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The material is sticky and toxic to other insects.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] One of the terpenes in the secretion, pinene, functions as an alarm pheromone.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Seeds deter predation with combinations of toxic non-protein amino acids, cyanogenic glycosides, protease and amylase inhibitors, and phytohemagglutinins.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] A few vertebrate species such as the Texas horned lizard are able to shoot squirts of blood from their eyes, by rapidly increasing the blood pressure within the eye sockets, if threatened.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Because an individual may lose up to 53% of blood in a single squirt, this is only used against persistent predators like foxes, wolves and coyotes (Canidae), as a last defence.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Canids often drop horned lizards after being squirted, and attempt to wipe or shake the blood out of their mouths, suggesting that the fluid has a foul taste; they choose other lizards if given the choice, suggesting a learned aversion towards horned lizards as prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The slime glands along the body of the hagfish secrete enormous amounts of mucus when it is provoked or stressed.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The gelatinous slime has dramatic effects on the flow and viscosity of water, rapidly clogging the gills of any fish that attempt to capture hagfish; predators typically release the hagfish within seconds.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Common predators of hagfish include seabirds, pinnipeds and cetaceans, but few fish, suggesting that predatory fish avoid hagfish as prey.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In communal defence, prey groups actively defend themselves by grouping together, and sometimes by attacking or mobbing a predator, rather than allowing themselves to be passive victims of predation.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Mobbing is the harassing of a predator by many prey animals.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Mobbing is usually done to protect the young in social colonies.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] For example, red colobus monkeys exhibit mobbing when threatened by chimpanzees, a common predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The male red colobus monkeys group together and place themselves between predators and the group's females and juveniles.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The males jump together and actively bite the chimpanzees.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Fieldfares are birds which may nest either solitarily or in colonies.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Within colonies, fieldfares mob and defecate on approaching predators, shown experimentally to reduce predation levels.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Some birds and insects use defensive regurgitation to ward off predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The northern fulmar vomits a bright orange, oily substance called stomach oil when threatened.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The stomach oil is made from their aquatic diets.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] It causes the predator's feathers to mat, leading to the loss of flying ability and the loss of water repellency.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This is especially dangerous for aquatic birds because their water repellent feathers protect them from hypothermia when diving for food.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] European roller chicks vomit a bright orange, foul smelling liquid when they sense danger.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] This repels prospective predators and may alert their parents to danger: they respond by delaying their return.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Numerous insects utilize defensive regurgitation.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The eastern tent caterpillar regurgitates a droplet of digestive fluid to repel attacking ants.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Similarly, larvae of the noctuid moth regurgitate when disturbed by ants.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The vomit of noctuid moths has repellent and irritant properties that help to deter predator attacks.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] An unusual type of predator deterrence is observed in the Malaysian exploding ant.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Social hymenoptera rely on altruism to protect the entire colony, so the self-destructive acts benefit all individuals in the colony.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] When a worker ant's leg is grasped, it suicidally expels the contents of its hypertrophied submandibular glands, expelling corrosive irritant compounds and adhesives onto the predator.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] These prevent predation and serve as a signal to other enemy ants to stop predation of the rest of the colony.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The normal reaction of a prey animal to an attacking predator is to flee by any available means, whether flying, gliding, falling, swimming, running, jumping, burrowing or rolling, according to the animal's capabilities.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Escape paths are often erratic, making it difficult for the predator to predict which way the prey will go next: for example, birds such as snipe, ptarmigan and black-headed gulls evade fast raptors such as peregrine falcons with zigzagging or jinking flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In the tropical rain forests of Southeast Asia in particular, many vertebrates escape predators by falling and gliding.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Among the insects, many moths turn sharply, fall, or perform a powered dive in response to the sonar clicks of bats.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Among fish, the stickleback follows a zigzagging path, often doubling back erratically, when chased by a fish-eating merganser duck.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Some animals are capable of autotomy (self-amputation), shedding one of their own appendages in a last-ditch attempt to elude a predator's grasp or to distract the predator and thereby allow escape.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] The lost body part may be regenerated later.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] Aristotle recorded observations (around 350 BC) of the antipredator behaviour of cephalopods in his *History of Animals*, including the use of ink as a distraction, camouflage, and signalling.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] In 1940, Hugh Cott wrote a compendious study of camouflage, mimicry, and aposematism, *Adaptive Coloration in Animals*.
[src:jet-propulsion/anti-predator-adaptation] By the 21st century, adaptation to life in cities had markedly reduced the antipredator responses of animals such as rats and pigeons; similar changes are observed in captive and domesticated animals.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming has evolved repeatedly in unrelated lineages.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Supposed jellyfish fossils occur in the Ediacaran, but the first free-swimming animals appear in the Early to Middle Cambrian.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] These are mostly related to the arthropods, and include the Dinocaridids, which swam by means of lateral lobes in a fashion reminiscent of today's cuttlefish and rays.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Cephalopods joined the ranks of the active swimmers (nekton) in the late Cambrian, and chordates were probably swimming from the Early Cambrian.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Many terrestrial animals retain some capacity to swim; some have returned to the water and developed the capacities for aquatic locomotion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Most apes (including humans) have lost the swimming instinct.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Microbial swimmers, sometimes called microswimmers, are microscopic entities that have the ability to move in fluid or aquatic environment.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They are found everywhere among microorganisms, such as bacteria, archaea, protists, sperm and microanimals.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Many small organisms such as bacteria have flagella which enable them to move in liquid environments.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They use the protons of an electrochemical gradient to move their flagella.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Torque in the flagella of bacteria is created by particles that conduct protons around the base of the flagellum.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The direction of rotation of the flagella comes from the occupancy of the proton channels along the perimeter of the flagellar motor.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Rod-shaped bacteria swim using rotating flagella.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Ciliates such as *Paramecium* use small flagella called cilia to move through the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] One ciliate may have hundreds to thousands of cilia, densely packed together in arrays.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] During movement, an individual cilium deforms using a high-friction power stroke followed by a low-friction recovery stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The deformation of each cilium is in phase with the deformation of its neighbor, propagating deformation waves along the surface of the organism.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] These waves of cilia, displaying collective behavior in a metachronal rhythm, allow the organism to move using the cilia in a coordinated manner.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] *Paramecium* can propel through water at up to 500 micrometers per second.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some bacteria can move by twitching and gliding, without using flagella.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Twitching depends on the extension, attachment to a surface, and retraction of type IV pili which pull the cell forwards in a manner similar to the action of a grappling hook, providing energy to move the cell forward.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Bacterial gliding uses different motor complexes, such as the focal adhesion complexes of *Myxococcus*.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Movement using a pseudopod is accomplished through increases in pressure at one point on the cell membrane.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This pressure increase is the result of actin polymerization between the cortex and the membrane.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] As the pressure increases the cell membrane is pushed outward creating the pseudopod.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] When the pseudopod moves outward, the rest of the body is pulled forward by cortical tension.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The result is cell movement through the fluid medium.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Furthermore, the direction of movement is determined by chemotaxis.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] When chemoattraction occurs in a particular area of the cell membrane, actin polymerization can begin and move the cell in that direction.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] An excellent example of an organism that utilizes pseudopods is *Naegleria fowleri*.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Jet propulsion is a method of aquatic locomotion where animals fill a muscular cavity and squirt out water to propel them in the opposite direction of the squirting water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Most organisms are equipped with one of two designs for jet propulsion; they can draw water from the rear and expel it from the rear, such as jellyfish, or draw water from front and expel it from the rear, such as salps.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Filling up the cavity causes an increase in both the mass and drag of the animal.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Consequently, the animal's velocity fluctuates as it moves through the water, accelerating while expelling water and decelerating while vacuuming water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Even though these fluctuations in drag and mass can be ignored if the frequency of the jet-propulsion cycles is high enough, jet propulsion is a relatively inefficient method of aquatic locomotion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] All cephalopods can move by jet propulsion, a very energy-consuming way to travel compared to the tail propulsion used by fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The relative efficiency of jet propulsion decreases further as animal size increases.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Since the Paleozoic, as competition with fish produced an environment where efficient motion was crucial to survival, jet propulsion has taken a back role, with fins and tentacles used to maintain a steady velocity.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The stop-start motion provided by the jets, however, continues to be useful for providing bursts of high speed – not least when capturing prey or avoiding predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Indeed, it makes cephalopods the fastest marine invertebrates.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Most cephalopods float (i.e. are neutrally buoyant), so do not need to swim to remain afloat.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Jellyfish use a one-way water cavity design which generates a phase of continuous cycles of jet-propulsion followed by a rest phase.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They move through the water by radially expanding and contracting their bell-shaped bodies to push water behind them.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They pause between the contraction and expansion phases to create two vortex rings.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Muscles are used for the contraction of the body, which creates the first vortex and pushes the animal forward, but the mesoglea is so elastic that the expansion is powered exclusively by relaxing the bell, which releases the energy stored from the contraction.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Meanwhile, the second vortex ring starts to spin faster, sucking water into the bell and pushing against the centre of the body, giving a secondary and "free" boost forward.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The mechanism, called passive energy recapture, only works in relatively small jellyfish moving at low speeds, allowing the animal to travel 30 percent farther on each swimming cycle.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Jellyfish achieved a 48 percent lower cost of transport (food and oxygen intake versus energy spent in movement) than other animals in similar studies.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] One reason for this is that most of the gelatinous tissue of the bell is inactive, using no energy during swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Scallops swim by slowly opening the gape of their two half-shells (called valves) and rapidly clapping them together.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Closing the valves propels water with a strong force near the hinge via the velum, a curtain-like fold of the mantle that directs water expulsion around the hinge.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They can swim both forwards and backwards.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Each colony member is a barrel-shaped zooid that can pump water from an inlet at one end to an outlet at the other end.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] A salp colony consists of a chain of zooids, and thus propels itself with multiple small jets of water, operating asynchronously (not in time with each other).
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This produces a relatively steady swimming speed, which is more efficient than a single pulsed jet.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Many fish swim through water by creating undulations with their bodies or oscillating their fins.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The undulations create components of forward thrust complemented by a rearward force, side forces which are wasted portions of energy, and a normal force that is between the forward thrust and side force.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Different fish swim by undulating different parts of their bodies.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Eel-shaped fish undulate their entire body in rhythmic sequences.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Streamlined fish, such as salmon, undulate the caudal portions of their bodies.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some fish, such as sharks, use stiff, strong fins to create dynamic lift and propel themselves.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] It is common for fish to use more than one form of propulsion, although one mode of swimming is dominant in each species.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Gait changes have even been observed in juvenile reef fish of various sizes.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Depending on their needs, fish can rapidly alternate between synchronized fin beats and alternating fin beats.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Crocodiles and amphibians such as newts, as well as amphibian tadpole larvae, use their deep, laterally compressed tails in an essentially carangiform mode of propulsion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Terrestrial snakes, in spite of their 'bad' hydromechanical shape with roughly circular cross-section and gradual posterior taper, swim fairly readily when required, by anguilliform propulsion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Cheloniidae (sea turtles) have forelimbs adapted into flippers of high-aspect-ratio wing shape, with which they propel themselves in a bird's propulsive mode, as if flying through the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some slow-swimming fish propel themselves by oscillating their fins.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Frogs and toads lose the larval tail completely.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] It is a rather efficient form of aquatic locomotion in shallow, slow-flowing waters because the legs are better streamlined for short accelerations, and the movements are "amphibious", i.e. the same jumping motion can also be used on land without needing to evolve a separate locomotive mechanism.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some arthropods, such as lobsters and shrimps, can propel themselves backwards quickly by flicking their tail, known as lobstering or the caridoid escape reaction.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some bony fish use fast-starts to escape from predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Fast-starts are characterized by the muscle contraction on one side of the fish, twisting the fish into a C-shape.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Afterwards, muscle contraction occurs on the opposite side to allow the fish to enter into a steady swimming state with waves of undulation traveling alongside the body.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The power of the bending motion comes from fast-twitch muscle fibers in the central region of the fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The signal to perform this contraction comes from a set of Mauthner cells which simultaneously send a signal to the muscles on one side of the fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Mauthner cells are activated when something such as a visual stimulus startles the fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Fast-starts are split up into three stages.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Stage one, the preparatory stroke, is characterized by the initial bending to a C-shape with small delay caused by hydrodynamic resistance.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Stage two, the propulsive stroke, involves the body bending rapidly to the other side, which may occur multiple times.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Stage three, the rest phase, cause the fish to return to normal steady-state swimming and the body undulations begin to cease.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Large muscles closer to the central portion of the fish are stronger and generate more force than the muscles in the tail.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This asymmetry in muscle composition causes body undulations that occur in Stage 3.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Once the fast-start is completed, the position of the fish has been shown to have a certain level of unpredictability, which helps fish survive against predators.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The rate at which the body can bend is limited by resistance contained in the inertia of each body part.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This inertia assists the fish in creating propulsion from the momentum created against the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The forward propulsion created from C-starts, and steady-state swimming in general, is a result of the body of the fish pushing against the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Waves of undulation create rearward momentum against the water providing the forward thrust required to push the fish forward.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] where U1=free stream velocity and U2=jet velocity.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] A good efficiency for carangiform propulsion is between 50 and 80%.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Pressure differences occur outside the boundary layer of swimming organisms due to disrupted flow around the body.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The difference on the up- and down-stream surfaces of the body is pressure drag, which creates a downstream force on the object.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Frictional drag, on the other hand, is a result of fluid viscosity in the boundary layer.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Higher turbulence causes greater frictional drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Reynolds number (Re) is the measure of the relationships between inertial and viscous forces in flow ((animal's length x animal's velocity)/kinematic viscosity of the fluid).
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Turbulent flow can be found at higher Re values, where the boundary layer separates and creates a wake, and laminar flow can be found at lower Re values, when the boundary layer separation is delayed, reducing wake and kinetic energy loss to opposing water momentum.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The body shape of a swimming organism affects the resulting drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Long, slender bodies reduce pressure drag by streamlining, while short, round bodies reduce frictional drag; therefore, the optimal shape of an organism depends on its niche.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming organisms with a fusiform shape are likely to experience the greatest reduction in both pressure and frictional drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Friction is created when molecules of the fluid collide with the swimming organism.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This causes drag, which is why many fish are streamlined in shape.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Streamlined shapes reduce drag by orienting elongated objects parallel to the force of drag, allowing the current to pass over and taper off the end of the fish, making swimming more efficient.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some flat-shaped fish can take advantage of pressure drag by having a flat bottom surface and a curved top surface.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This provides upward lift during swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Lift-powered swimming can be compared to flying as appendages flap like wings.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Drag powered swimming can be compared to oars rowing a boat, with movement in a horizontal plane, or paddling, with movement in the parasagittal plane.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Drag swimmers use a cyclic motion, pushing water back in a power stroke, and return their limbs forward in the return or recovery stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Pushing water directly backwards moves their body forward, while the return stroke tends to oppose forward motion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Reducing drag on the return stroke is essential for efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] For example, ducks paddle through the water spreading the webs of their feet for the power stroke, and pull their webs together to reduce the pull of water forward on the return stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The legs of water beetles have hairs which spread out to catch and move water back in the power stroke, but lay flat for the return stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Also, one side of a water beetle leg is wider than the others and is held perpendicular to the motion when pushing backward, but the leg rotates when the limb returns forward, so the thinner side catches less water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Drag swimming is less efficient than lift-powered swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Semi-aquatic animals experience more drag than fully aquatic animals.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Design that allows them to function out of the water limits the efficiency possible to be reached when in the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] In water swimming at the surface exposes them to resistive wave drag and is associated with a higher cost than submerged swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming below the surface exposes them to resistance due to return strokes and pressure, but primarily friction.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Frictional drag is due to fluid viscosity and body morphology.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Pressure drag is due to the difference of water flow around the body and is also affected by body morphology.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The fur of otters and beavers, for example, is useful on land but decreases streamlining and creates additional drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The platypus may be a good example of an intermediate between drag and lift swimmers because it has a rowing mechanism similar to lift-based pectoral oscillation.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The limbs of semi-aquatic organisms are reserved for use on land and using them in water not only increases the cost of locomotion, but limits them to drag-based modes.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Although they are less efficient, drag swimmers are able to produce more thrust at low speeds than lift swimmers.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] They are also thought to be more maneuverable due to the large thrust produced.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Many aquatic/marine organisms have developed organs to compensate for their weight and control their buoyancy in the water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] These structures make the density of their bodies very close to that of the surrounding water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some hydrozoans, such as siphonophores, have gas-filled floats; the Nautilus, Sepia, and Spirula (Cephalopods) have chambers of gas within their shells; and most teleost fish and many lantern fish (Myctophidae) are equipped with swim bladders.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Many aquatic and marine organisms may also be composed of low-density materials.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Deep-water teleosts, which do not have a swim bladder, have few lipids and proteins, deeply ossified bones, and watery tissues that maintain their buoyancy.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some sharks' livers are composed of low-density lipids, such as hydrocarbon squalene or wax esters (also found in Myctophidae without swim bladders), which provide buoyancy.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming animals that are denser than water must generate lift or adapt a benthic lifestyle.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Movement of the fish to generate hydrodynamic lift is necessary to prevent sinking.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Often, their bodies act as hydrofoils, a task that is more effective in flat-bodied fish.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] At a small tilt angle, the lift is greater for flat fish than it is for fish with narrow bodies.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Narrow-bodied fish use their fins as hydrofoils while their bodies remain horizontal.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] In sharks, the heterocercal tail shape drives water downward, creating a counteracting upward force while thrusting the shark forward.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The lift generated is assisted by the pectoral fins and upward-angle body positioning.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] It is supposed that tunas primarily use their pectoral fins for lift.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Buoyancy maintenance is metabolically expensive.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Growing and sustaining a buoyancy organ, adjusting the composition of biological makeup, and exerting physical strain to stay in motion demands large amounts of energy.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] It is proposed that lift may be physically generated at a lower energy cost by swimming upward and gliding downward, in a "climb and glide" motion, rather than constant swimming on a plane.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Temperature can greatly affect the ability of aquatic organisms to move through water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This is because temperature not only affects the properties of the water, but also the organisms in the water, as most have an ideal range specific to their body and metabolic needs.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Q10 (temperature coefficient), the factor by which a rate increases at a 10 °C increase in temperature, is used to measure how organisms' performance relies on temperature.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Most have increased rates as water becomes warmer, but some have limits to this and others find ways to alter such effects, such as by endothermy or earlier recruitment of faster muscle.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] For example, *Crocodylus porosus*, or estuarine crocodiles, were found to increase swimming speed from 15 °C to 23 °C and then to have peak swimming speed from 23 °C to 33 °C.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] However, performance began to decline as temperature rose beyond that point, showing a limit to the range of temperatures at which this species could ideally perform.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] The more of the animal's body that is submerged while swimming, the less energy it uses.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming on the surface requires two to three times more energy than when completely submerged.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This is because of the bow wave that is formed at the front when the animal is pushing the surface of the water when swimming, creating extra drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Some terrestrial animals among the tetrapods and the insects have secondarily adapted to life in water, including evolving adaptations to aquatic locomotion.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] While tetrapods lost many of their natural adaptations to swimming when they evolved onto the land, many have re-evolved the ability to swim or have indeed returned to a completely aquatic lifestyle.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Primarily or exclusively aquatic animals have re-evolved from terrestrial tetrapods multiple times: examples include amphibians such as newts, reptiles such as crocodiles, snakes, sea turtles, and ichthyosaurs, marine mammals such as whales, and birds such as penguins.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Among invertebrates, aquatic insects include water boatmen and diving beetles, which have adapted their hind legs for use as rowing oars for swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] In the beetles, one pair of legs is so modified; among the water boatmen (corixid bugs), two pairs of legs have scoop- or oar-shaped tarsi.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] In 2013, the scholar of human evolution Pedro Renato Bender proposed that the swimming instinct was lost as a consequence of constraints related to arboreal life in the last common ancestor of apes.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] This has been called the Saci last common ancestor hypothesis, after Saci, a Brazilian folklore character who cannot cross water.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Bender hypothesized that the ancestral ape increasingly avoided deep-water bodies when the risks of being exposed to water were clearly higher than the advantages of crossing them.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] A decreasing contact with water bodies could then have led to the disappearance of the doggy paddle instinct.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Swimming has been known amongst humans since prehistoric times; the earliest record of swimming dates back to Stone Age paintings from around 7,000 years ago.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] Competitive swimming started in Europe around 1800 and was part of the first modern 1896 Summer Olympics in Athens, though not in a form comparable to the contemporary events.
[src:jet-propulsion/aquatic-locomotion] It was not until 1908 that regulations were implemented by the International Swimming Federation to produce competitive swimming.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The operations of *Ars Technica* are funded primarily by advertising, and it has offered a paid subscription service since 2001.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Ken Fisher, who serves as the website's current editor-in-chief, and Jon Stokes created *Ars Technica* in 1998.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Its purpose was to publish computer hardware and software-related news articles and guides; in their words, "the best multi-OS, PC hardware, and tech coverage possible while ... having fun, being productive, and being as informative and as accurate as possible".
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] "Ars technica" is a Latin phrase that translates to "Art of Technology".
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The website published news, reviews, guides, and other content of interest to computer enthusiasts.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Writers for *Ars Technica* were geographically distributed across the United States at the time; Fisher lived in his parents' house in Boston, Stokes in Chicago, and the other writers in their respective cities.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] On May 19, 2008, *Ars Technica* was sold to Condé Nast Digital, the online division of Condé Nast Publications.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The sale was part of a purchase by Condé Nast Digital of three unaffiliated websites costing $25 million in total: *Ars Technica*, Webmonkey, and *HotWired*.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] *Ars Technica* was added to the company's *Wired* Digital group, which included *Wired* and Reddit.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] In an interview with *The New York Times*, Fisher said other companies offered to buy *Ars Technica* and the site's writers agreed to a deal with Condé Nast because they felt it offered them the best chance to turn their "hobby" into a business.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Fisher, Stokes, and the eight other writers at the time were employed by Condé Nast.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Layoffs at Condé Nast in November 2008 affected websites owned by the company "across the board", including *Ars Technica*.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] On May 5, 2015, *Ars Technica* launched its United Kingdom site to expand its coverage of issues related to the UK and Europe.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The UK site began with around 500,000 readers and had reached roughly 1.4 million readers a year after its launch.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] In September 2017, Condé Nast announced that it was significantly downsizing its *Ars Technica* UK arm, and laid off all but one member of its permanent editorial staff.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Since 2024, Condé Nast, *Ars Technica*'s parent company, has entered a bilateral deal with OpenAI.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] On February 13, 2026, *Ars Technica* published an article on how an AI agent seemingly wrote a hit piece on a software maintainer after the maintainer rejected the agent's code.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The article was retracted the same day after several of the quotes that were falsely attributed to the maintainer were found to be fabricated by AI.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] One of the journalists who wrote the article was subsequently fired from *Ars Technica*.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The content of articles published by *Ars Technica* has generally remained the same since its creation in 1998 and is categorized by four types: news, guides, reviews, and features.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] *Ars Technica* also hosts OpenForum, a free Internet forum for the discussion of a variety of topics.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Originally, most news articles published by the website were aggregated from other technology-related websites.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] *Ars Technica* provided short commentaries on the news, generally a few paragraphs, and a link to the original source.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] After being purchased by Condé Nast, *Ars Technica* began publishing more original news, investigating topics, and interviewing sources themselves.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] A significant portion of the news articles published there now are original.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Relayed news is still published on the website, ranging from one or two sentences to a few paragraphs.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] On September 12, 2012, *Ars Technica* recorded its highest daily traffic ever with its iPhone 5 event coverage.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] It recorded 15.3 million page views, 13.2 million of which came from its live blog platform of the event.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Jennifer Ouelette, the former science editor of Gizmodo, contributes science and culture coverage.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Beth Mole, who has a PhD in microbiology, handles *Ars*' health coverage.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] She was formerly at *Science News.* Eric Berger, formerly of the *Houston Chronicle*, covers space exploration.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] John Timmer is the science editor for *Ars.* He formerly taught scientific writing and science journalism at Stony Brook University and Weill Cornell Medical College.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] He earned his undergraduate degree from Columbia University and his PhD from University of California, Berkeley and worked as a postdoc at Memorial Sloan Kettering.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Benj Edwards worked for *Ars* as senior AI reporter until March 2026, when he was fired over his role in the publication of a now-retracted article that included AI-generated quotes.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The cost of operating *Ars Technica* has always been funded primarily by advertising.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Originally handled by Federated Media Publishing, selling advertising space on the website is now managed by Condé Nast.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] In addition to online advertising, *Ars Technica* has sold subscriptions to the website since 2001, now named Ars Pro and Ars Pro++ subscriptions (previously known as Ars Premier).
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Subscribers are not shown advertisements, and receive benefits including the ability to see exclusive articles, post in certain areas of the *Ars Technica* forum, and participate in live chat rooms with notable people in the computer industry.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] To a lesser extent, revenue is also collected from content sponsorship.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] A series of articles about the future of collaboration was sponsored by IBM, and the site's Exploring Datacenters section is sponsored by data-management company NetApp.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] *Ars Technica* also collects revenue from affiliate marketing by advertising deals and discounts from online retailers, and from the sale of *Ars Technica*-branded merchandise.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] On March 5, 2010, *Ars Technica* experimentally blocked readers who used Adblock Plus—one of several computer programs that stop advertisements from being displayed in a web browser—from viewing the website.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Fisher estimated 40% of the website's readers had the software installed at the time.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] The block and article were controversial, generating articles on other websites about them, and the broader issue of advertising ethics.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] Readers of *Ars Technica* generally followed Fisher's persuasion; the day after his article was published, 25,000 readers who used the software had allowed the display of advertisements on *Ars Technica* in their browser, and 200 readers had subscribed to Ars Premier.
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] In February 2016, Fisher noted, "That article lowered the ad-block rate by 12 percent, and what we found was that the majority of people blocking ads on our site were doing it because other sites were irritating them".
[src:jet-propulsion/ars-technica] In response to increasing use of ad blockers, *Ars Technica* intends to identify readers who filter out advertisements and ask them to support the site by several means.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] An **axial compressor** is a type of gas compressor that continuously pressurizes a working fluid.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] It is a rotating, airfoil-based device in which the fluid flows primarily in one direction parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This distinguishes axial compressors from other types of rotating compressors, such as centrifugal compressors, axi-centrifugal compressors, and mixed-flow compressors, in which the fluid flowing includes a significant radial component directed outward from the axis of rotation.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The rotor blades exert torque on the fluid, increasing its energy as it passes through the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The stationary blades, or stators, slow the fluid, converting the circumferential component of flowing into pressure.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Compressors are typically driven by an electric motor, a steam turbine, or a gas turbine.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Axial flow compressors produce a continuous flow of compressed gas.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] They exhibit high efficiency and large mass flow rate in relation to the size of their cross-section.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] They are more intricate and expensive relative to other designs, requiring several rows of airfoils to achieve a large pressure rise.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Axial compressors are integral to the design of large gas turbines such as jet engines, high speed ship engines, and small scale power stations.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] They are also used in industrial applications such as large volume air separation plants, blast furnace air, fluid catalytic cracking air, and propane dehydrogenation.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Additionally, due to their performance and operability across the flight envelope (safe operational limits for an aircraft), they are widely used in aerospace applications.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Axial compressors consist of alternating rows of rotating and stationary airfoils.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The rotating airfoils, or rotors, are mounted on a rotating drum, which is driven by a central shaft.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The stationary airfoils, known as vanes or stators, are mounted to a tubular casing.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] One row of rotors and one row of stators together form a stage.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The rotors impart kinetic energy to the working fluid, increasing its velocity in the axial and circumferential directions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The stators convert the increased kinetic energy into static pressure through diffusion and redirect the flow direction of the fluid to prepare it for the rotor blades of the next stage.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The area between the rotor drum and casing decreases along the flow direction to maintain an optimum Mach number as the fluid is compressed.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Rotor passages can be designed to achieve diffusive pressure rise, leading to a higher pressure rise per stage.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The ratio of pressure rise in the rotor to the total pressure rise of the stage is known as the degree of reaction.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The increase in pressure produced by a single stage is limited by the relative velocity between the rotor and the fluid, and the turning and diffusion capabilities of the airfoils.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] A typical stage in a commercial compressor will produce a pressure increase of between 15% and 60% (pressure ratios of 1.15–1.6) at design conditions with a polytropic efficiency in the region of 90–95%.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] To achieve different pressure ratios, axial compressors are designed with different numbers of stages and rotational speeds.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] As a rule of thumb, it can be assumed that each stage in a given compressor has the same temperature rise (ΔT).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Therefore, at the entry, temperature (Tstage) to each stage must increase progressively through the compressor and the ratio (Delta T)/(Tstage) entry must decrease, thus implying a progressive reduction in stage pressure ratio through the unit.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Hence the rear stage develops a significantly lower pressure ratio than the first stage.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Higher stage pressure ratios are also possible if the relative velocity between fluid and rotors is supersonic, but this is achieved at the expense of efficiency and operability.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Such compressors, with stage pressure ratios of over 2, are only used where minimizing the compressor size, weight or complexity is critical, such as in military jets.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The airfoil profiles are optimized and matched for specific velocities and turning.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Although compressors can be run at other conditions with different flows, speeds, or pressure ratios, this can result in an efficiency penalty or even a partial or complete breakdown in flow (known as compressor stall and pressure surge respectively).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Thus, a practical limit on the number of stages, and the overall pressure ratio, comes from the interaction of the different stages when required to work away from the design conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] These "off-design" conditions can be mitigated to a certain extent by providing some flexibility in the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This is achieved normally through the use of adjustable stators or with valves that can bleed fluid from the main flow between stages (inter-stage bleed).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Modern jet engines use a series of compressors, running at different speeds; to supply air at around 40:1 pressure ratio for combustion with sufficient flexibility for all flight conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The law of moment of momentum states that the sum of the moments of external forces acting on a fluid which is temporarily occupying the control volume is equal to the net change of angular momentum flux through the control volume.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The swirling fluid enters the control volume at radius, $r_{1}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w1}\,$ , and leaves at radius, $r_{2}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w2}\,$ .
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] are the absolute velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] are the axial flow velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] are the swirl velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] are the blade-relative velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Axial compressor performance is shown on a compressor map, also known as a characteristic, by plotting pressure ratio and efficiency against corrected mass flow at different values of corrected compressor speed.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Axial compressors, particularly near their design point are usually amenable to analytical treatment, and a good estimate of their performance can be made before they are first run on a rig.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The compressor map shows the complete running range, i.e. off-design, of the compressor from ground idle to its highest corrected rotor speed, which for a civil engine may occur at top-of-climb, or, for a military combat engine, at take-off on a cold day.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Not shown is the sub-idle performance region needed for analysing normal ground and in-flight windmill start behaviour.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Stage pressure ratio against flow rate is lower than for a no-loss stage as shown.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Losses are due to blade friction, flow separation, unsteady flow and vane-blade spacing.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The performance of a compressor is defined according to its design.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] But in actual practice, the operating point of the compressor deviates from the design point; this is known as *off-design operation*.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The value of $(\tan \beta _{2}+\tan \alpha _{1})\,$ doesn't change for a wide range of operating points till stalling.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Also $\alpha _{1}=\alpha _{3}\,$ because of minor change in air angle at rotor and stator, where $\alpha _{3}\,$ is diffuser blade angle.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] for positive values of J, slope of the curve is negative and vice versa.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] There are multiple modes of instability an axial compressor could undergo.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Edward Greitzer used a Helmholtz resonator type of compression system model to predict the transient response of a compression system after a small perturbation superimposed on a steady operating condition.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] He found a non-dimensional parameter which predicted which mode of compressor instability, rotating stall or surge, would result.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The parameter used the rotor speed, the Helmholtz resonator frequency of the system, and an "effective length" of the compressor duct.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] These produced a critical value which predicted either rotating stall or surge where the slope of pressure ratio against flow changed from negative to positive.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In the plot of pressure-flow rate, the line separating graph between two regions – unstable and stable – is known as the **surge line**.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This line is formed by joining surge points at different rotational speeds.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Surging is the unstable flow in axial compressors due to complete breakdown of the steady through flow.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This phenomenon affects the performance of compressor and is undesirable.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The following explanation for surging refers to running a compressor at a constant speed on a rig and gradually reducing the exit area by closing a valve.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] What happens, i.e. crossing the surge line, is caused by the compressor trying to deliver air, still running at the same speed, to a higher exit pressure.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Suppose the initial operating point *D* ( ${\dot {m}},P_{D}\,$ ) at some rotational speed *N*.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] On decreasing the flow-rate at same rotational speed along the characteristic curve by partial closing of the valve, the pressure in the pipe increases which will be taken care by increase in input pressure at the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] With further increase in pressure up to point *P* (surge point), compressor pressure will increase.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Further moving towards left keeping rotational speed constant, pressure in pipe will increase but compressor pressure will decrease leading to back air flow towards the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Due to this back flow, pressure in pipe will decrease because this unequal pressure condition cannot stay for a long period of time.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Though valve position is set for lower flow rate say point *G* but compressor will work according to normal stable operation point say *E*, so path *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*E* will be followed leading to breakdown of flow, hence pressure in the compressor falls further to point *H*( $P_{H}\,$ ).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This increase and decrease of pressure in pipe will occur repeatedly in pipe and compressor following the cycle *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*H*–*E* also known as the surge cycle.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This phenomenon will cause vibrations in the whole machine and may lead to mechanical failure.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] That is why left portion of the curve from the surge point is called unstable region and may cause damage to the machine.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] So the recommended operation range is on the right side of the surge line.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Stall is a phenomenon affecting the performance of the compressor whereby flow separation occurs at the compressor blades, leading to reduced compression and a drop in engine power.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] An analysis is made of rotating stall in compressors of many stages, finding conditions under which a flow distortion can occur which is steady in a traveling reference frame, even though upstream total and downstream static pressure are constant.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In the compressor, a pressure-rise hysteresis is assumed.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Two types of stall are distinguished: *positive stall,* where flow separation occurs on the suction side of the blade, and *negative stall,* where it occurs on the pressure side.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In practice, negative stall is negligible compared to positive stall as flow separation is least likely to occur on the pressure side of the blade.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In a multi-stage compressor, at the high pressure stages, axial velocity is very small.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Stalling value decreases with a small deviation from the design point causing stall near the hub and tip regions whose size increases with decreasing flow rates.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] They grow larger at very low flow rate and affect the entire blade height.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Non-uniformity of air flow in the rotor blades may disturb local air flow in the compressor without upsetting it.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The compressor continues to work normally but with reduced compression.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Thus, rotating stall decreases the effectiveness of the compressor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In a rotor with blades moving say towards right.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Let some blades receives flow at higher incidence, this blade will stop positively.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] It creates obstruction in the passage between the blade to its left and itself.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Thus the left blade will receive the flow at higher incidence and the blade to its right with decreased incidence.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The left blade will experience more stall while the blade to its right will experience lesser stall.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Towards the right stalling will decrease whereas it will increase towards its left.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Movement of the rotating stall can be observed depending upon the chosen reference frame.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] From an energy exchange point of view axial compressors are reversed turbines.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Steam-turbine designer Charles Algernon Parsons, for example, recognized that a turbine which produced work by virtue of a fluid's static pressure (i.e. a reaction turbine) could have its action reversed to act as an air compressor, calling it a turbo compressor or pump.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] His rotor and stator blading described in one of his patents had little or no camber although in some cases the blade design was based on propeller theory.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The machines, driven by steam turbines, were used for industrial purposes such as supplying air to blast furnaces.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Parsons supplied the first commercial axial flow compressor for use in a lead smelter in 1901.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Parsons' machines had low efficiencies, later attributed to blade stall, and were soon replaced with more efficient centrifugal compressors.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Brown Boveri & Cie produced "reversed turbine" compressors, driven by gas turbines, with blading derived from aerodynamic research which were more efficient than centrifugal types when pumping large flow rates of 40,000 ft3/min (19 m3/s) at pressures up to 45 psi (310 kPa).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Because early axial compressors were not efficient enough a number of papers in the early 1920s claimed that a practical axial-flow turbojet engine would be impossible to construct.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Griffith published a seminal paper in 1926, noting that the reason for the poor performance was that existing compressors used flat blades and were essentially "flying stalled".
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] He showed that the use of airfoils instead of the flat blades would increase efficiency to the point where a practical jet engine was a real possibility.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] He concluded the paper with a basic diagram of such an engine, which included a second turbine that was used to power a propeller.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Although Griffith was well known due to his earlier work on metal fatigue and stress measurement, little work appears to have started as a direct result of his paper.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The only obvious effort was a test-bed compressor built by Hayne Constant, Griffith's colleague at the Royal Aircraft Establishment.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Other early jet efforts, notably those of Frank Whittle and Hans von Ohain, were based on the more robust and better understood centrifugal compressor which was widely used in superchargers.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Griffith had seen Whittle's work in 1929 and dismissed it, noting a mathematical error, and going on to claim that the frontal size of the engine would make it useless on a high-speed aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Real work on axial-flow engines started in the late 1930s, in several efforts that all started at about the same time.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In England, Hayne Constant reached an agreement with the steam turbine company Metropolitan-Vickers (Metrovick) in 1937, starting their turboprop effort based on the Griffith design in 1938.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In 1940, after the successful run of Whittle's centrifugal-flow design, their effort was re-designed as a pure jet, the Metrovick F.2.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In the United States, both Lockheed and General Electric were awarded contracts in 1941 to develop axial-flow engines, the former a pure jet, the latter a turboprop.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Northrop also started their own project to develop a turboprop, which the US Navy eventually contracted in 1943.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Westinghouse also entered the race in 1942, their project proving to be the only successful one of the US efforts, later becoming the J30.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] As Griffith had originally noted in 1929, the large frontal size of the centrifugal compressor caused it to have higher drag than the narrower axial-flow type.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Additionally the axial-flow design could improve its compression ratio simply by adding additional stages and making the engine slightly longer.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In the centrifugal-flow design the compressor itself had to be larger in diameter, which was much more difficult to fit properly into a thin and aerodynamic aircraft fuselage (although not dissimilar to the profile of radial engines already in widespread use).
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] On the other hand, centrifugal-flow designs remained much less complex (the major reason they "won" in the race to flying examples) and therefore have a role in places where size and streamlining are not so important.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In the jet engine application, the compressor faces a wide variety of operating conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] On the ground at high power settings the inlet pressure is high, inlet speed zero, and the compressor spun at a variety of speeds as the power is applied.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Once in flight the inlet pressure drops, but the inlet speed increases (due to the forward motion of the aircraft) to recover some of this pressure, and the compressor tends to run at a single speed for long periods of time.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] There is simply no "perfect" compressor for this wide range of operating conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Fixed geometry compressors, like those used on early jet engines, are limited to a design pressure ratio of about 4:1 or 5:1.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] As with any heat engine, fuel efficiency is strongly related to the compression ratio, so there is very strong financial need to improve the compressor stages beyond these sorts of ratios.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Additionally the compressor may stall if the inlet conditions change abruptly, a common problem on early engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In some cases, if the stall occurs near the front of the engine, all of the stages from that point on will stop compressing the air.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In this situation the energy required to run the compressor drops suddenly, and the remaining hot air in the rear of the engine allows the turbine to speed up the whole engine dramatically.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This condition, known as surging, was a major problem on early engines and often led to the turbine or compressor breaking and shedding blades.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] For all of these reasons, axial compressors on modern jet engines are considerably more complex than those on earlier designs.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] All compressors have an optimum point relating rotational speed and pressure, with higher compressions requiring higher speeds.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Early engines were designed for simplicity, and used a single large compressor spinning at a single speed.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Later designs added a second turbine and divided the compressor into low-pressure and high-pressure sections, the latter spinning faster.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This *two-spool* design, pioneered on the Bristol Olympus, resulted in increased efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Further increases in efficiency may be realised by adding a third spool, but in practice the added complexity increases maintenance costs to the point of negating any economic benefit.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] That said, there are several three-spool engines in use, perhaps the most famous being the Rolls-Royce RB211 (and its successor, the Rolls-Royce Trent), used on a wide variety of commercial aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] As an aircraft changes speed or altitude, the pressure of the air at the inlet to the compressor will vary.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] In order to "tune" the compressor for these changing conditions, designs starting in the 1950s would "bleed" air out of the middle of the compressor in order to avoid trying to compress too much air in the final stages.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] This was also used to help start the engine, allowing it to be spun up without compressing much air by bleeding off as much as possible.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Bleed systems were already commonly used anyway, to provide airflow into the turbine stage where it was used to cool the turbine blades, as well as provide pressurized air for the air conditioning systems inside the aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] A more advanced design, the *variable stator*, used blades that can be individually rotated around their axis, as opposed to the power axis of the engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] For start up they are rotated to "closed", reducing compression, and then are rotated back into the airflow as the external conditions require.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The General Electric J79 was the first major example of a variable stator design, and today it is a common feature of most military engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Closing the variable stators progressively, as compressor speed falls, reduces the slope of the surge (or stall) line on the operating characteristic (or map), improving the surge margin of the installed unit.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] By incorporating variable stators in the first five stages, General Electric Aircraft Engines has developed a ten-stage axial compressor capable of operating at a 23:1 design pressure ratio.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The relative motion of the blades to the fluid adds velocity or pressure or both to the fluid as it passes through the rotor.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The fluid velocity is increased through the rotor, and the stator converts kinetic energy to pressure energy.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Some diffusion also occurs in the rotor in most practical designs.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The increase in velocity of the fluid is primarily in the tangential direction (swirl) and the stator removes this angular momentum.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The pressure rise results in a stagnation temperature rise.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] For a given geometry the temperature rise depends on the square of the tangential Mach number of the rotor row.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Current turbofan engines have fans that operate at Mach 1.7 or more, and require significant containment and noise suppression structures to reduce blade loss damage and noise.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] A map shows the performance of a compressor and allows determination of optimal operating conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] It shows the mass flow along the horizontal axis, typically as a percentage of the design mass flow rate, or in actual units.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] The pressure rise is indicated on the vertical axis as a ratio between inlet and exit stagnation pressures.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] A surge or stall line identifies the boundary to the left of which the compressor performance rapidly degrades and identifies the maximum pressure ratio that can be achieved for a given mass flow.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Contours of efficiency are drawn as well as performance lines for operation at particular rotational speeds.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Operating efficiency is highest close to the stall line.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] If the downstream pressure is increased beyond the maximum possible the compressor will stall and become unstable.
[src:jet-propulsion/axial-flow-compressor] Typically the instability will be at the Helmholtz frequency of the system, taking the downstream plenum into account.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The **Boeing 787 Dreamliner**, often shortened to **Boeing 787**, is an American wide-body airliner developed and manufactured by Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] After dropping its unconventional Sonic Cruiser project, Boeing announced the conventional **7E7** on January 29, 2003, which focused largely on efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The program was launched on April 26, 2004, with an order for 50 aircraft from All Nippon Airways (ANA), targeting a 2008 introduction.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On July 8, 2007, a prototype 787 without major operating systems was rolled out; subsequently the aircraft experienced multiple delays, until its maiden flight on December 15, 2009.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Type certification was received in August 2011, and the first 787-8 was delivered in September 2011 and entered commercial service in October 2011, with ANA.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] At launch, Boeing targeted the 787 with 20% less fuel burn compared to aircraft like the Boeing 767.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] It could carry 200 to 300 passengers on point-to-point routes up to 8,500 nautical miles [nmi] (15,700 km; 9,800 mi), a shift from hub-and-spoke travel.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The twinjet is powered by General Electric GEnx or Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 high-bypass turbofans.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] It is the first airliner with an airframe primarily made of composite materials and makes greater use of electrical systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Externally, it is recognizable by its four-window cockpit, raked wingtips, and noise-reducing chevrons on its engine nacelles.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Development and production rely on subcontractors around the world more than for previous Boeing aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Since March 2021, final assembly has been at the Boeing South Carolina factory; it was formerly in the Boeing Everett Factory in Washington state.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The stretched 787-9, 206 ft (63 m) long, can fly 7,565 nmi (14,010 km; 8,706 mi) with 296 passengers; it entered service on August 7, 2014, with All Nippon Airways.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Early 787 operations encountered several problems caused mainly by its lithium-ion batteries, including fires onboard some aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In January 2013, the US FAA grounded all 787s until it approved the revised battery design in April 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Significant quality control issues from 2019 onward caused a production slowdown and, from January 2021 until August 2022, an almost total cessation of deliveries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The first fatal crash and hull loss of the aircraft occurred on June 12, 2025, with Air India Flight 171.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] A preliminary report issued on July 12 by the Indian Aircraft Accident Investigation Bureau did not recommend any actions to Boeing, or 787 operators.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing has spent $32 billion on the program; estimates for the number of aircraft sales needed to break even vary between 1,300 and 2,000.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As of May 2026, the 787 program has received 2,434 orders and made 1,276 deliveries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] During the late 1990s, slowing sales of the 767 and 747-400 prompted Boeing to consider replacing them.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Two proposals were made: the 747X would have lengthened the 747-400 and improved its efficiency, and the Sonic Cruiser would have achieved 15% higher speeds (approximately Mach 0.98) while burning fuel at the same rate as the 767.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Market interest for the 747X proposal was tepid; several major American airlines, including Continental Airlines, showed initial enthusiasm for the Sonic Cruiser, although concerns about its operating cost were expressed.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The global airline market was disrupted by the 9/11 attacks and increased petroleum prices, making airlines more interested in efficiency than speed.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The worst-affected airlines, those in the United States, had been considered the most likely customers for the Sonic Cruiser; thus the Sonic Cruiser was officially canceled on December 20, 2002.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On January 29, 2003, Boeing announced another product, the 7E7, that would use Sonic Cruiser technology in a more conventional configuration.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The emphasis on a smaller midsize twinjet rather than a large 747-size aircraft represented a shift from the hub-and-spoke theory toward the point-to-point theory, in response to analysis of focus groups.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In 2003, James McNerney, who was then a relatively new member of Boeing's board of directors, supported the idea for a new aircraft to regain market share from Airbus.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The project to replace the Sonic Cruiser was named "7E7" (with a development code name of "Y2").
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Technology from the Sonic Cruiser and 7E7 was to be used as part of Boeing's project to replace its entire airliner product line, an endeavor called the Yellowstone Project (of which the 7E7 became the first stage).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Early concept images of the 7E7 included rakish cockpit windows, a dropped nose, and a distinctive "shark-fin" tail.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The "E" was said to stand for various things, such as "efficiency" or "environmentally friendly".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In the end, Boeing said it stood for "Eight".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In July 2003, a public naming competition was held for the 7E7, for which out of 500,000 votes cast online the winning title was *Dreamliner*.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Other names included *eLiner*, *Global Cruiser*, and *Stratoclimber*.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On April 26, 2004, Japanese airline All Nippon Airways (ANA) became the launch customer for the 787, announcing a firm order for 50 aircraft with deliveries to begin in late 2008.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787-3 and 787-8 were to be the initial variants, with the 787-9 entering service in 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 5, 2012, Indian state carrier Air India became the first carrier to take possession of a Dreamliner that was manufactured in the Charleston, South Carolina, Boeing plant.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] This was the first 787 that was manufactured outside of Washington.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing would go on to use both the Everett and South Carolina plants to deliver the Dreamliner.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 was the first production airliner built with a fuselage comprising one-piece composite barrel sections instead of aluminum-sheet assemblies using many fasteners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing selected two new engines to power the 787, the Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 and General Electric GEnx.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing stated the 787 would be approximately 20 percent more fuel-efficient than the 767, with approximately 40 percent of the efficiency gain from the engines, plus gains from aerodynamic improvements, increased use of lighter-weight composite materials, and advanced systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The airframe underwent extensive structural testing during its design.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787-8 and -9 were intended to have a certified 330-minute ETOPS capability, but entered service with 180 minutes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] 330-minute certification was delayed until 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] During the design phase, the 787 underwent extensive wind tunnel testing at Boeing's Transonic Wind Tunnel, QinetiQ's five-meter wind tunnel at Farnborough, United Kingdom, and NASA Ames Research Center's wind tunnel, as well as at the French aerodynamics research agency, ONERA.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The final styling was more conservative than earlier proposals, with the fin, nose, and cockpit windows changed to a more conventional form.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By 2005, customer-announced orders and commitments for the 787 reached 237 aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing initially priced the 787-8 variant at US$120 million, a low figure that surprised the industry.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By 2007, the list price had increased to US$157–167 million, eventually exceeding US$200 million by the time the aircraft received type certification.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Airlines and lessors do not pay the full list price, with market prices for the 787-8 being up to 46% lower.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On December 16, 2003, Boeing announced that the 787 would be assembled in its factory in Everett, Washington.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Instead of conventionally building the aircraft from the ground up, the final assembly employed 800 to 1,200 people to join completed subassemblies and integrate systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing assigned global subcontractors to do more assembly work, delivering completed subassemblies to Boeing for final assembly.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] This approach was intended to result in a leaner, simpler assembly line and lower inventory, with pre-installed systems reducing final assembly time by three-quarters to three days.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Subcontractors had early difficulties procuring needed parts and finishing subassemblies on schedule, leaving remaining assembly work for Boeing to complete as "traveled work".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In 2010, Boeing considered in-house construction of the 787-9 tail; the tail of the 787-8 is made by Alenia.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 was unprofitable for some subcontractors; Alenia's parent company, Finmeccanica, had a total loss of €750 million on the project.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] To speed up deliveries, Boeing modified four used 747-400s into 747 Dreamlifters to transport 787 wings, fuselage sections, and other smaller parts.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Japanese industrial participation was key to the project.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Japanese companies co-designed and built 35% of the aircraft; the first time that outside firms played a key design role on Boeing airliner wings.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The Japanese government supported development with an estimated US$2 billion in loans.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On April 26, 2006, Japanese manufacturer Toray Industries and Boeing signed a production agreement involving US$6 billion worth of carbon fiber, extending a 2004 contract.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In May 2007, the final assembly on the first 787 began at Everett.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] From the outset, 787 chief engineer Walt Gillette and his colleagues realized that the "Working Together" approach to supplier coordination used for the 777 must substantially evolve for the 787.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] So they created the 787 Dreamliner Partner Council.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The council evolved from the Sonic Cruiser effort and a similar approach used in Boeing's defense business unit.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The partner council would make 787 decisions together, a departure from Boeing's more hierarchical approach to decision making for the 777.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing harnessed not only expertise from the Partner Council, but also benefited from cross-cultural collaboration, according to Walt Gillette, as quoted in *The Culture of Collaboration* (2024, expanded and updated edition) by Evan Rosen.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing worked to reduce excess weight since assembly of the first airframe began; in late 2006, the first six 787s were overweight, with the first aircraft 5,000 lb (2,300 kg) heavier than required.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The seventh and subsequent aircraft would be the first 787-8s expected to meet the weight requirement.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Accordingly, some parts were redesigned to include more use of titanium.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In July 2015, Reuters reported that Boeing was considering reducing the use of titanium to reduce the construction cost.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Early built 787s (line numbers under 20) were overweight, increasing their fuel burn and reducing their maximum range, and some carriers decided to take later aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing struggled to sell these aircraft, eventually offering significant discounts and scrapping one.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Because of their line numbers, these aircraft were nicknamed the "Terrible Teens".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing planned the first flight by the end of August 2007 and premiered the first 787 (registered N787BA) at a rollout ceremony on July 8, 2007.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 had 677 orders at this time, which is more orders from launch to roll-out than any previous wide-body airliner.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The major systems were not installed at the time; many parts were attached with temporary non-aerospace fasteners requiring replacement with flight fasteners later.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In September 2007, Boeing announced a three-month delay, blaming a shortage of fasteners as well as incomplete software.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 10, 2007, a second three-month delay to the first flight and a six-month delay to first deliveries were announced due to supply chain problems, a lack of documentation from overseas suppliers, and flight guidance software delays.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Less than a week later, Mike Bair, the 787 program manager, was replaced.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On January 16, 2008, Boeing announced a third three-month delay to the first flight of the 787, citing insufficient progress on "traveled work".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On March 28, 2008, to gain more control over the supply chain, Boeing announced plans to buy Vought Aircraft Industries' interest in Global Aeronautica; a later agreement was also made to buy Vought's factory in North Charleston.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On April 9, 2008, a fourth delay was announced, shifting the maiden flight to the fourth quarter of 2008, and delaying initial deliveries by around 15 months to the third quarter of 2009.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787-9 variant was postponed to 2012 and the 787-3 variant was to follow at a later date.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On November 4, 2008, a fifth delay was announced due to incorrect fastener installation and the Boeing machinists strike, stating that the first test flight would not occur in the fourth quarter of 2008.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] After assessing the program schedule with suppliers, in December 2008, Boeing stated that the first flight was delayed until the second quarter of 2009.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Airlines, such as United Airlines and Air India, stated their intentions to seek compensation from Boeing for the delays.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] A secondary factor in the delays faced by the 787 program was the lack of detailed specifications provided to partners and suppliers.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In previous programs Boeing had supplied high level design data, but for the 787, decided to provide broad level specifications only, on the assumption that relevant partners had the competencies to perform the design and integration work with the limited data.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] This decision created several delays as suppliers struggled to work with the limited design data.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As Boeing worked with its suppliers toward production, the design proceeded through a series of test goals.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] While critics had expressed concerns that a composite fuselage could shatter and burn with toxic fumes during crash landings, test data indicated no greater toxicity than conventional metal airframes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The crash test was the third in a series of demonstrations conducted to match FAA requirements, including additional certification criteria due to the wide-scale use of composite materials.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 meets the FAA's requirement that passengers have at least as good a chance of surviving a crash landing as they would with current metal airliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On August 7, 2007, on-time certification of the Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 engine by European and US regulators was received.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The alternative GE GEnx-1B engine achieved certification on March 31, 2008.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On June 20, 2008, the first aircraft was powered up, for testing the electrical supply and distribution systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] A non-flightworthy static test airframe was built; on September 27, 2008, the fuselage was successfully tested to a differential pressure of 14.9 psi (103 kPa), which is 150 percent of the maximum pressure expected in commercial service.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In December 2008, the 787's maintenance program was passed by the FAA.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On May 3, 2009, the first test 787 was moved to the flight line following extensive factory testing, including landing gear swings, systems integration verification, and a total run-through of the first flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On May 4, 2009, a press report indicated a 10–15% range reduction, about 6,900 nmi (12,800 km; 7,900 mi) instead of the originally promised 7,700 to 8,200 nautical miles (14,300 to 15,200 km; 8,900 to 9,400 mi), for early aircraft that were about 8% overweight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Substantial redesign work was expected to correct this, which would complicate increases in production rates; Boeing stated the early 787-8s would have a range of almost 8,000 nmi (15,000 km; 9,200 mi).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As a result, some airlines reportedly delayed deliveries of 787s to take later planes that may be closer to the original estimates.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing expected to have the weight issues addressed by the 21st production model.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On June 15, 2009, during the Paris Air Show, Boeing said that the 787 would make its first flight within two weeks.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On June 23, the first flight was postponed due to structural reasons.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing provided an updated 787 schedule on August 27, 2009, with the first flight planned to occur by the end of 2009 and deliveries to begin at the end of 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The company expected to write off US$2.5 billion because it considered the first three Dreamliners built unsellable and suitable only for flight tests.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 28, 2009, Boeing selected Charleston, SC as the site for a second 787 production line, after soliciting bids from multiple states.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On December 12, 2009, the first 787 completed high-speed taxi tests, the last major step before flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On December 15, 2009, Boeing conducted the 787-8 maiden flight from Paine Field in Everett, Washington, at 10:27 am PST and landed three hours later at 1:33 p.m. at Seattle's Boeing Field.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] During the flight the 787 reached a top speed of 180 kn (333 km/h) and maximum altitude of 13,200 ft (4,000 m).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Originally scheduled for ⁠5+1/2⁠ hours, the test flight was shortened to three hours due to unfavorable weather conditions.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The six-aircraft ground and flight test program was scheduled to be done in eight and a half months and 6800 hours, which was the fastest certification campaign for a new Boeing commercial design.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The flight test program comprised six aircraft, ZA001 through ZA006, four with Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 engines and two with GE GEnx-1B64 engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The second 787, ZA002 in All Nippon Airways livery, flew to Boeing Field on December 22, 2009, to join the flight test program; the third 787, ZA004 made its first flight on February 24, 2010, followed by ZA003 on March 14, 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On March 24, 2010, flutter and ground effects testing was completed, clearing the aircraft to fly its entire flight envelope.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On March 28, 2010, the 787 completed the ultimate wing load test, which requires that the wings of a fully assembled aircraft be loaded to 150% of the design limit load and held for 3 seconds.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The wings were flexed approximately 25 ft (7.6 m) upward during the test.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Unlike past aircraft, the wings were not tested to failure.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On April 7, data showed the test had been a success.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On April 23, 2010, the newest 787, ZA003, arrived at the McKinley Climatic Laboratory hangar at Eglin Air Force Base, Florida, for extreme weather testing in temperatures ranging from 115 to −45 °F (46 to −43 °C), including takeoff preparations at both temperature extremes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] ZA005, the fifth 787 and the first with GEnx engines, began ground engine tests in May 2010, and made its first flight on June 16, 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In June 2010, gaps were discovered in the horizontal stabilizers of test aircraft due to improperly installed shims; all aircraft were inspected and repaired.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] That same month, a 787 experienced its first in-flight lightning strike; inspections found no damage.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As composites can have as little as 1/1,000th the electrical conductivity of aluminum, conductive material is added to alleviate potential risks and to meet FAA requirements.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The FAA also planned requirement changes to help the 787 show compliance.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In December 2019, it was reported that Boeing had removed the copper foil that formed part of the protection against lightning strikes to the wings of the aircraft; it then worked with the FAA to override concerns raised.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 made its first appearance at an international air show at the Farnborough Airshow, United Kingdom, on July 18, 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On August 2, 2010, a Trent 1000 engine suffered an uncontained failure at Rolls-Royce's test facility during ground testing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The failure changed the schedule for installing Trent 1000 engines; on August 27, 2010, Boeing stated that the first delivery to launch customer ANA would be delayed until early 2011.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] That same month, Boeing faced compensation claims from airlines owing to ongoing delivery delays.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In September 2010, it was reported that two additional 787s might join the test fleet for a total of eight flight test aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On September 10, 2010, a partial engine surge occurred in a Trent engine on ZA001 at Roswell.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 4, 2010, the sixth 787, ZA006 joined the test program with its first flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On November 9, 2010, the second 787, ZA002 made an emergency landing at Laredo International Airport, Texas, after smoke and flames were detected in the main cabin during a test flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The electrical fire caused some systems to fail before landing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Following this incident, Boeing suspended flight testing on November 10, 2010; ground testing continued.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] After investigation, the in-flight fire was primarily attributed to foreign object debris (FOD) that was present in the electrical bay.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] After electrical system and software changes, the 787 resumed flight testing on December 23, 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On November 5, 2010, it was reported that some 787 deliveries would be delayed to address problems found during flight testing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In January 2011, the first 787 delivery was rescheduled to the third quarter of 2011 due to software and electrical updates following the in-flight fire.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By February 24, 2011, the 787 had completed 80% of the test conditions for the Rolls-Royce Trent 1000 engine and 60% of the conditions for the General Electric GEnx-1B engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In July 2011, ANA performed a week of operations testing using a 787 in Japan.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The test aircraft had flown 4,828 hours in 1,707 flights combined by August 15, 2011.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] During testing, the 787 visited 14 countries in Asia, Europe, North America, and South America to test in extreme climates and conditions and for route testing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On August 13, 2011, certification testing of the Rolls-Royce powered 787-8 finished.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The FAA and European Aviation Safety Agency certified the 787 on August 26, 2011, at a ceremony in Everett, Washington.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Certification cleared the way for deliveries and in 2011, Boeing prepared to increase 787 production rates from two to ten aircraft per month at assembly lines in Everett and Charleston over two years.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Legal difficulties clouded production at Charleston; on April 20, 2011, the National Labor Relations Board alleged that a second production line in South Carolina violated two sections of the National Labor Relations Act.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In December 2011, the National Labor Relations Board dropped its lawsuit after the Machinists' union withdrew its complaint as part of a new contract with Boeing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The first 787 assembled in South Carolina was rolled out on April 27, 2012.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The first 787 was officially delivered to All Nippon Airways (ANA) on September 25, 2011, at the Boeing Everett factory.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] A ceremony to mark the occasion was also held the next day.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On September 27, it flew to Tokyo Haneda Airport.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The airline took delivery of the second 787 on October 13, 2011.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 26, 2011, an ANA 787 flew the first commercial flight from Tokyo's Narita International Airport to Hong Kong International Airport.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The Dreamliner entered service some three years later than originally planned.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Tickets for the flight were sold in an online auction; the highest bidder had paid $34,000 for a seat.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] An ANA 787 flew its first long-haul flight to Europe on January 21, 2012, from Haneda to Frankfurt Airport.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Even after production of the 787 began, Boeing continued to produce the 767 as a freighter.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] More stringent emissions and noise limits will go into effect in 2028 and prevent 767 sales in its current form.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] To address this concern, Boeing has widely reported to be working on a freighter version of the 787, showing proposals to customers including FedEx Express.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As of May 2024, production of the 787 Freighter is expected to begin between 2028 and 2033.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In April 2008, to keep the -8 on track for delivery, the -9 stretch was postponed from 2010 to at least 2012 and prioritized before the 787-3 and its 43 orders to follow without a firm delivery date.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] It kept the -8 length but its 51.7 m wingspan would have fit in ICAO Aerodrome Reference Code D.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] It was designed to operate on Boeing 757-300/Boeing 767-200 sized regional routes from airports with restricted gate spacing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The wingspan was decreased by using blended winglets instead of raked wingtips.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By January 2010, all orders, from Japan Airlines and All Nippon Airways, had been converted to the 787-8.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] As it was designed specifically for the Japanese market, Boeing would likely scrap it after they switched orders.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The -8's longer wingspan makes it more efficient on stages longer than 200 nmi (370 km; 230 mi).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In December 2010, Boeing withdrew the short-haul model as it struggled to produce the 787-8 after program delays of three years.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The 787 Dreamliner program has reportedly cost Boeing $32 billion.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In 2013, the 787 program was expected to be profitable after 1,100 aircraft have been sold.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] At the end of 2013, the cost of producing a 787 exceeded the purchase price.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing's accounting method books sales immediately and distributes estimated production costs over ten years for the 1,300 aircraft it expects to deliver during that time.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] JPMorgan Chase analyst Joseph Nadol estimated the program's cash loss to be $45 million per airplane, decreasing as the program moves forward.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The actual cash flow reflects Boeing collecting most of the purchase price upon delivery; Boeing expects deferred costs to total $25 billion before the company begins to break even on production; the comparable number for the Boeing 777, adjusted for inflation, is $3.7 billion.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing lost $30 million per 787 delivered in the first quarter of 2015, although Boeing planned to break even by the end of the year.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The accumulated losses for the 787 totaled almost $27 billion (~$34.8 billion in 2024) by May 2015.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In the second quarter of 2015, Boeing lost $25 million (~$32.2 million in 2024) on each 787 delivered but was planning to break even per plane before the year-end.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] After that Boeing hoped to build 900 Dreamliners over six years at an average profit of more than $35 million each.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] But with deferred costs peaking in 2016 at $33 billion, (~$42.2 billion in 2024) Leeham analyst Bjorn Fehrm believes Boeing cannot make an overall profit on the program.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Ted Piepenbrock, an academic affiliated with MIT and the University of Oxford, projects losses decreasing through the first 700 airliners and forecasts the cumulative deferred costs to peak beyond $34 billion.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The model most favorable to Boeing projects a program loss of $5 billion after delivering 2,000 Dreamliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing's original development investment, estimated at least at a further $20 billion, is not included in these costs.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing is reaching it through a larger proportion of the 20% to 40% higher price -9/10s, costing only 5% to 10% more than the -8 with lower production costs from reliability and producibility investments and the expected experience curve.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Former Douglas Aircraft chief economist Adam Pilarski notes that two assembly sites slow the experience curve.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing assumed a faster improvement than on previous programs which had not happened.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Competition with the Airbus A350 and the launch of the A330neo put strong pressure on the 787 pricing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On July 21, 2016, Boeing reported charges of $847 million against two flight-test 787s built in 2009.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing had planned to refurbish and sell them but instead wrote them off as research and development expense.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In 2017, Boeing's Jim Albaugh said that the requested return on net assets (RONA) led to outsourcing systems reducing investment, but improving RONA had to be balanced against the risk of loss of control.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] From 2019, Boeing was to build 14 787s per month (168 per year), helping to offset the $28 billion in deferred production costs accumulated through 2015 and would add 100 aircraft to the current accounting block of 1,300 at the end of 2017 third quarter.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The valuation for a new 787-9 is $145 million in 2018, up from $135 million in 2014, but it may have been sold for $110–115 million to prevent A330neo sales while an A330-900 is worth $115 million.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In February 2018, Boeing priced six 787-9s for less than $100–115m each to Hawaiian Airlines, close to their production cost of $80–90m, to overcome its A330-800 order.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By late 2018, deferred production costs were reduced from a peak of $27.6 billion in early 2016 to $23.5 billion as assembly efficiency improved and the 800th production started.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By 2014, Boeing planned to improve financial return by reorganizing the production line, renegotiating contracts with suppliers and labor unions, and increasing the 787 production rate, stepwise, to 12 airplanes per month by the end of 2016 and 14 airplanes per month by the end of the decade.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By April 2015, the production rate was 10 per month.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] From late 2020, the production rate is to be reduced from 14 to 12 airplanes per month due to the China-United States trade war.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Production could be trimmed to 10 planes per month as demand for wide-body aircraft falters.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On October 1, 2020, Boeing announced the 787 would be produced only in North Charleston from mid-2021 due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation, as the production rate fell to six per month.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In December, the monthly rate was further reduced to five.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Early in 2020, Boeing engineers complained about depressions in the 787's vertical tail fin, affecting hundreds of planes or the vast majority of the fleet.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Workers in Charleston and Everett had improperly discarded shims before the final installation of fasteners, which could lead to structural failure under limited loads.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In late August 2020, Boeing grounded eight 787s due to such improper fuselage shimming and inner skin surfacing issues—issues which proved to have been discovered in August 2019 at Boeing South Carolina.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The different composite fuselage components on the 787 are joined together around the circumference using splice plates.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Small variations in the thickness of the fuselage skin may leave gaps between the splice plate and the inner skin of the fuselage.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] While most of the gaps are closed by fastener force during the joining process, any gaps that remain must be filled using shims, usually made of fiberglass.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Issues with this shimming process plagued numerous 787s and required expensive rework of assembled planes before delivery.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The FAA then began to inquire into the company's Quality Management System (QMS), which Boeing had previously argued justified a reduction of 900 quality inspectors, but which had failed to detect either the shim or skin surface issues.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] A third quality-control issue then emerged, this time with the 787's horizontal stabilizers, and affecting as many as 893 Dreamliners: workers in Salt Lake City had clamped portions of the tail section too tightly, which could lead to premature material fatigue.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] At this point Boeing expected a one-time inspection during regularly scheduled maintenance to address the issues and expected merely to slow 787 deliveries "in the near term".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] By January 2021, Boeing had halted 787 deliveries to complete the inspection relating to poor quality control, then in March the FAA withdrew Boeing's delegated authority to inspect and sign off on four new 787s, saying that it would extend this withdrawal to further aircraft if needed.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing briefly resumed deliveries on March 26, 2021, handing over one 787-9 to United Airlines, but deliveries ceased again in May 2021; meaning that almost all deliveries had been paused for nearly a year.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The delay generated $1 billion in abnormal costs and caused the company to cut production to around two planes a month.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On July 13, Boeing discovered gaps at joints in the forward pressure bulkhead and again reduced production; the company also investigated whether the issue affected 787s already in service.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Questions were asked about the inspection process used to check the work, and Boeing worked with the FAA to fix the problem, which was said to pose "no immediate threat to flight safety" and did not require 787s already in service to be grounded.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The rectification process for existing aircraft was made more complex by a lack of detailed configuration data on each aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The new problems and the extension of the 13 month long disruption to 787 deliveries led to anger from buyers; a slide in the company's stock price; and demands by a subcommittee of the US House of Representatives for a review of the FAA's oversight of the plane.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In January 2022, it was reported that deliveries were not anticipated to restart until April 2022.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In late March Boeing began sounding out suppliers about their ability to support the production of up to seven aircraft a month by late 2023.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Vistara, which had been expecting delivery of four Dreamliners in 2022, indicated a lack of confidence in Boeing meeting its delivery aims by arranging to lease aircraft instead.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Later in April reports began to emerge of a further delay of at least two months, and it was only in late April that Boeing submitted the necessary certification package laying out the inspections and repairs to be undertaken on already constructed planes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The FAA rejected portions of the package as incomplete and returned it to Boeing, indicating a further delay before the resumption of deliveries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In late July, the FAA approved Boeing's revised certification package, leading the company to anticipate resuming deliveries "within days".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Deliveries resumed on August 10, 2022, after the FAA granted clearance.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Between November 2020 and August 2022, only 14 787s were delivered.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In January 2023, Boeing stated that the 787 fuselage gap problem and the subsequent halt in deliveries had cost Boeing $6.3 billion in "abnormal costs".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In February 2023, a further problem, of an analysis error by a supplier related to the 787 forward pressure bulkhead, was identified, leading to a further temporary halt in deliveries (but not in production) and a 5% drop in the company's share price.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On March 10, the FAA approved the resumption of the deliveries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In April 2024, Boeing engineer Sam Salehpour alleged that the 787's (as well as the 777's) fuselage had been improperly assembled and that it could cause individual aircraft to break apart in mid-air.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Salehpour also claimed that he tried to raise these concerns to Boeing but was reprimanded by the company.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The FAA is investigating Salehpour's allegations.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing released a statement rejecting these claims.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] In early 2025, Italian authorities discovered a fraud scheme involving over 4,800 parts.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The investigation indicated that Manufacturing Process Specification (MPS), an Italian supplier, and its subcontractors had falsified quality certifications for the components used in the Dreamliner.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] MPS, however, no longer exists as a company.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Boeing announced in February 2025 that it had completed rework on the 122 787s that had to be stored long-term until the structural issues discovered in 2020 - shimming issues with the small gaps at the fuselage joins - could be repaired.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The last jet that exited the rework program in February 2025 was a 787-10 built in South Carolina in December 2020.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] The "shadow factory" rework program had pulled hundreds of mechanics away from regular production work.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] Increases to the maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) for the 787-9 and 787-10 had been planned since at least 2019, and Boeing formally acknowledged the planned Increased Ground Weight (IGW) variants in January 2022..
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On the 787-9, MTOW would increase by approximately 10,000 pounds (4,500 kg), enabling about 6,600 pounds (3 t) additional payload or more than 300 nautical miles (560 km) of additional range.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] On the 787-10, MTOW would increase by approximately 14,000 pounds (6,400 kg), enabling about 11,000 pounds (5 t) additional payload or more than 400 nautical miles (740 km) of additional range.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] These MTOW increases were approved by the FAA in March 2026.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p01] All 787-9s and 787-10s produced since December 2025 are structurally capable of the higher MTOW rating, though airlines may choose a lower MTOW certification as the certified operating weights may affect airport fees and route planning.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Boeing 787 Dreamliner is a long-haul, widebody, twin-engine jetliner, designed with lightweight structures that are 80% composite by volume; Boeing lists its materials by weight as 50% composite, 20% aluminum, 15% titanium, 10% steel, and 5% other materials.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Aluminum has been used throughout the leading edges of wings and tailplanes, titanium is predominantly present within the elements of the engines and fasteners, while various individual components are composed of steel.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] External features include a smooth nose contour, raked wingtips, and engine nacelles with noise-reducing serrated edges (chevrons).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The longest-range 787 variant can fly up to 7,565 nmi (14,010 km; 8,710 mi), or the even longer Qantas QF 9 flight between Perth and London Heathrow, over 7,828 nmi (14,497 km; 9,008 mi).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The aircraft has a design life of 44,000 flight cycles.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Among 787 flight systems, a key change from traditional airliners is the electrical architecture.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The architecture is bleedless and replaces bleed air with electrically powered compressors and four of six hydraulic power sources with electrically driven pumps while eliminating pneumatics and hydraulics from some subsystems, e.g. engine starters and brakes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing says that this system extracts 35% less power from the engines, allowing increased thrust and improved fuel efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Spoiler electromechanical actuators (SEMAs) control two of the seven spoiler pairs on each wing surface, providing roll control, air and ground speed brake, and droop capabilities similar to those provided by the hydraulic actuators used on the remaining spoiler surfaces.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The SEMAs are controlled by electronic motor control units (EMCUs).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The total available onboard electrical power is 1.45 megawatts, which is five times the power available on conventional pneumatic airliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Electrically powered systems include engine start, cabin pressurization, horizontal-stabilizer trim, and wheel brakes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Wing ice protection is another new system; it uses electro-thermal heater mats on the wing slats instead of traditional hot bleed air.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] An active gust alleviation system, similar to the system used on the B-2 bomber, improves ride quality during turbulence.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787 has a "fly-by-wire" control system similar in architecture to that of the Boeing 777.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The flight deck features multi-function LCDs, which use an industry-standard graphical user interface widget toolkit (Cockpit Display System Interfaces to User Systems / ARINC 661).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787 flight deck includes two head-up displays (HUDs) as a standard feature.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Like other Boeing airliners, the 787 uses a yoke (as opposed to a side-stick).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Under consideration is the future integration of forward-looking infrared into the HUD for thermal sensing, allowing pilots to "see" through clouds.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Lockheed Martin's Orion spacecraft will use a glass cockpit derived from Honeywell International's 787 flight deck systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] One of the two batteries weighs 28.5 kg and is rated 29.6 V, 76 Ah, giving 2.2 kWh.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Battery charging is controlled by four independent systems to prevent overcharging, following early lab testing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The battery systems were the focus of a regulatory investigation due to multiple lithium battery fires, which led to the grounding of the 787 fleet starting in January 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A version of Ethernet (Avionics Full-Duplex Switched Ethernet (AFDX) / ARINC 664) transmits data between the flight deck and aircraft systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The control, navigation, and communication systems are networked with the passenger cabin's in-flight internet systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In January 2008, FAA concerns were reported regarding possible passenger access to the 787's computer networks; Boeing has stated that various protective hardware and software solutions are employed, including air gaps to physically separate the networks, and firewalls for software separation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] These measures prevent data transfer from the passenger internet system to the maintenance or navigation systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787 is the first commercial aircraft to have an airframe majority made of carbon fiber reinforced polymer (CFRP), applied in: the empennage, fuselage, wings, doors, and in most other main components.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Each 787 contains approximately 77,000 lb (35 t) of CFRP, made with 51,000 lb (23 t) of pure carbon fiber.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] CFRP materials have a higher strength-to-weight ratio than conventional aluminum structural materials, which contributes significantly to the 787's weight savings, as well as superior fatigue behavior.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Historically, the first CFRP primary structure in Boeing commercial aircraft was put into service in 1984 on the horizontal tail of the Boeing 737 Classic, and in the mid-1990s on both vertical and horizontal tail (empennage) of the Boeing 777.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In the early 2000s, while studying the proposed Sonic Cruiser, Boeing built and tested the first CFRP fuselage section for commercial aircraft, to evaluate materials and manufacturing techniques which later applied to the Dreamliner.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Instead of designing one-piece composite fuselage barrels like the 787, the competing Airbus A350 uses a slightly more conventional approach with CFRP panels on CFRP frames, which is considered less risky in terms of assembly tolerance between fuselage sections.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Safety can be a concern due to lower impact energy absorption and poorer fire, smoke and toxicity capability of CFRP fuselages in the event of a crash landing, leading to whistleblower complaints at Boeing by Vince Weldon, who was fired in 2006.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) later denied Weldon whistleblower status "largely on the grounds that Boeing's 787 design does not violate any FAA regulations or standards".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing further argued that CFRP structures have been used on empennages and other parts of airliners for many years without incident, and special damage detection procedures will be instituted for the 787 to detect any potential hidden damage.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In the fall of 2004, 787 engineering program leader Walt Gillette made the final decision to use CFRP for the 787's fuselage, a first for a commercial aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Two distinct Boeing sub-groups with expertise in two different materials—CFRP and aluminum alloy—spent months researching how their material would perform for the 787.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Therefore, a "fundamental philosophical dichotomy" existed in the group.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This is why a single "collaborative" leader rather than the group needed to make the final call on the material.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2006, Boeing launched the 787 GoldCare program.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This is an optional, comprehensive life-cycle management service, whereby aircraft in the program are routinely monitored and repaired, as needed.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Although the first program of its kind from Boeing, post-sale protection programs are not new; such programs are usually offered by third party service centers.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing is also designing and testing composite hardware so inspections are mainly visual.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This reduces the need for ultrasonic and other non-visual inspection methods, saving time and money.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Boeing 787 is equipped with two flight recorders—a Forward Flight Recorder (FWD FR) and an Aft Flight Recorder (AFT FR)—each of which units provides the functions traditionally provided by the Flight Data Recorder and the Cockpit Voice Recorder.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-8 is designed to typically seat 234 passengers in a three-class setup, 240 in two-class domestic configuration, and 296 passengers in a high-density economy arrangement.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Seat rows can be arranged in four to seven abreast in first, business, or premium economy—e.g., 1–⁠2–⁠1, 2–⁠2–⁠2, or 2–⁠3–⁠2.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Eight or nine abreast are options in economy—e.g., 2–⁠4–⁠2 or 3–⁠3–⁠3.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Typical seat room ranges from 46 to 61 in (120 to 150 cm) pitch in first, 36 to 39 in (91 to 99 cm) in business, and 32 to 34 in (81 to 86 cm) in economy.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Cabin interior width is approximately 18 feet (550 cm) at armrest level.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Dreamliner's cabin width is 15 inches (38 cm) more than that of the Airbus A330 and A340, 5 inches (13 cm) less than the A350, and 16 in (41 cm) less than the 777.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's economy seats can be up to 17.5 in (44.4 cm) wide for nine-abreast seating and up to 19 inches (48 cm) wide for eight-abreast seating arrangements.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Most airlines are selecting the nine-abreast (3–3–3) configuration.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's nine-abreast seating for economy provides passengers less space, particularly across the hips and shoulders, than any other jet airliner.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Some observers recommended passengers avoid flying 787s with nine-abreast seating, although others suggested that the 787 is more comfortable than other airliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's cabin windows have dimensions of 10.7 by 18.4 in (27 by 47 cm), and a high eye level so passengers can maintain a view of the horizon.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The composite fuselage permits larger windows without the need for structural reinforcement.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] While the lavatory window also uses smart glass, it was given a traditional sunshade.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's cabin features light-emitting diodes (LEDs) as standard equipment, allowing the aircraft to be entirely "bulbless".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] LED lights have previously been an option on the Boeing 777 and Airbus aircraft fitted with standard fluorescent lights.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The system has three-color LEDs plus a white LED.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787 interior was designed to better accommodate persons with mobility, sensory, and cognitive disabilities.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] For example, a 56 by 57 in (140 by 140 cm) convertible lavatory includes a movable center wall that allows two separate lavatories to become one large wheelchair-accessible facility.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's internal cabin pressure is the equivalent of a 6,000 feet (1,800 m) cabin altitude, which is a higher pressure than the 8,000 feet (2,400 m) cabin altitude of older conventional aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] According to Boeing, in a joint study with Oklahoma State University, this significantly improves passenger comfort.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Cabin air pressurization is provided by electrically driven compressors, rather than traditional engine-bleed air, thereby eliminating the need to cool heated air before it enters the cabin.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The cabin's humidity is programmable based on the number of passengers carried and allows 15% humidity settings instead of the 4% found in previous aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The composite fuselage avoids metal fatigue issues associated with higher cabin pressure and eliminates the risk of corrosion from higher humidity levels.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Boeing 787 has two engine options: the General Electric GEnx-1B and the Rolls-Royce Trent 1000.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of early 2020, of the 1,484 total 787 orders, 905 (61%) had selected General Electric engines, 476 (32%) had chosen Rolls-Royce engines, and 103 (7%) remained undecided.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Both engines use a standardized electrical interface, enabling airlines to install either model with minimal modifications.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This interchangeability reduces the time and cost typically associated with switching engine types and is particularly attractive to lessors, as it allows airlines to maintain a common engine type across their fleet when an aircraft changes ownership.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] While earlier aircraft could accommodate engines from different manufacturers, swaps were rarely performed due to their complexity and expense.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787's engines use an all-electric, bleedless system, adapted from the Sonic Cruiser, that eliminates the need for traditional superheated air conduits used for de-icing, cabin pressurization, and other functions.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As part of its "Quiet Technology Demonstrator 2" program, Boeing integrated several noise-reduction features into the aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] These include an air inlet lined with sound-absorbing materials and an exhaust duct with a chevron-toothed pattern to promote quieter mixing of exhaust with ambient air.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing says these technologies make the 787 significantly quieter both inside the cabin and in surrounding areas, with sound levels kept below 85 decibels at airport boundaries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2016, Rolls-Royce began flight testing the Trent 1000 TEN engine, an upgraded version of the Trent 1000 featuring a new compressor system derived from the Trent XWB and a new turbine design for extra thrust, up to 78,000 lbf (350 kN).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This flight surpassed the previous record of 9,127 nautical miles (16,903 km; 10,503 mi), set in 2002 by an Airbus A330.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Dreamliner then continued eastbound from Dhaka to return to Boeing Field, setting a world-circling speed record of 42 hours, 27 minutes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In December 2011, Boeing started a six-month promotion 787 world tour, visiting various cities in China, Africa, the Middle East, Europe, United States, and others.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In April 2012, an ANA 787 made a delivery flight from Boeing Field to Haneda Airport partially using biofuel from cooking oil.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] 25% said they would go out of their way to again fly on the 787.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Other 787 operators have reported similar fuel savings, ranging from 20 to 22% compared with the 767-300ER.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] An analysis by consultant AirInsight concluded that United Airlines' 787s achieved an operating cost per seat that was 6% lower than the Airbus A330.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In November 2017, International Airlines Group chief Willie Walsh said that for its budget carrier Level the lower cost of ownership of its two A330-200 more than offsets the 13,000 lb (6 t) higher fuel burn ($3,500 on a Barcelona-Los Angeles flight).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It would introduce three more A330s as there were not enough 787 pilots.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Early operators discovered that if the APS5000 Auxiliary power unit was shut down with the inlet door closed, heat continued to build up in the tail compartment and cause the rotor shaft to bow.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It could take up to two hours for the shaft to straighten again.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This was particularly acute on short haul flights as there was insufficient time to allow the unit to cool before a restart was needed.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Procedures were modified and the APU was later redesigned to address the issue.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On September 15, 2012, the NTSB requested the grounding of certain 787s due to GE engine failures; GE believed the production problem had been fixed by that time.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In March 2014, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries informed Boeing of a new problem that was caused by a change in manufacturing processes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Employees did not fill gaps with shims to connect wing rib aluminum shear ties to the carbon composite wing panels; the tightened fasteners, without shims, cause excessive stress that creates hairline cracks in the wings, which could enlarge and cause further damage.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Forty-two aircraft awaiting delivery were affected, and each required one to two weeks to inspect and repair.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing did not expect this problem to affect the overall delivery schedule, even if some airplanes were delivered late.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Dispatch reliability is an industry standard measure of the rate of departure from the gate with no more than 15 minutes delay due to technical issues.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-8 started out with a ~96% operational reliability, increasing to ~98.5% in April 2015.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Daily utilization increased from five hours in 2013 to twelve hours in 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Dispatch reliability grew to 99.3% in 2017.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Airlines have often assigned the 787 to routes previously flown by larger aircraft that could not return a profit.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] For example, Air Canada offered a Toronto-Pearson to New Delhi route, first utilizing a Lockheed L1011, then a Boeing 747-400, then an Airbus A340-300, but none of these types were efficient enough to generate profit.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The airline operated the route profitably with a 787-9, and credits the right number of seats and greater fuel efficiency for this success.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Up to June 30, 2017, after 565 units were delivered since 2011: 60% -8 (340) and 40% -9 (225), the airports with most 787 departures are Haneda Airport with 304 weekly, Narita Airport with 276 and Doha Airport with 265.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By the end of 2017, there were 39 airlines operating the 787 on 983 routes with an average length of 5,282 km (2,852 nmi; 3,282 mi), including 163 new routes (17%).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of 24 March 2018, the 787's longest route is Qantas' Perth-London Heathrow, a distance of 14,499 km (7,829 nmi; 9,009 mi) and the second-longest regular scheduled flight behind Qatar Airways' 14,529 km (7,845 nmi; 9,028 mi) route from Doha to Auckland, flown with a Boeing 777-200LR.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2023, the first 787s to be withdrawn from commercial service, two 10-year-old -8s, were torn down by Irish company EirTrade Aviation, as they would otherwise have shortly required 12-year checks and landing-gear overhauls.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The used parts were in high demand amid the post-pandemic global shortage.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] There is no obvious recycling path for the carbon composite airframe.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The shortest Dreamliner variant, the 787-8 was the first variant to fly in December 2009, then the longer 787-9 in September 2013, followed by the longest variant, the 787-10, in March 2017.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] These variants are called *B788*, *B789*, and *B78X*, respectively in the list of ICAO aircraft type designators.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The short-range 787-3 was canceled in 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] With a typical capacity of 248 passengers and a range of 7,305 nautical miles (13,529 km; 8,406 mi), the -8 is the base model of the 787 family and was the first to enter service in 2011.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-8 is targeted to replace the Boeing 767-200ER as well as expand into new non-stop markets where larger planes would not be economically viable.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of January 2023, approximately 26% of 787 orders are for the 787-8 with 386 delivered.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2018, Boeing said it would change the -8 manufacturing to raise its commonality with the -9 above the current 30% to be more like the 95% commonality between the -9 and -10, as it will benefit from learning from those.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] When it was launched, a new 787-8 was to cost only slightly more than the 767-300ER, valued new for $85 million at its 1990s peak, but it ended being 20% more costly.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It competes with the Airbus A330-200 and Airbus A330-800.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It features active boundary-layer control on the tail surfaces, reducing drag.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-9 is targeted to replace the Boeing 767-300ER.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It competes with the Airbus A330-300 and Airbus A330-900.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2005, the entry into service (EIS) was planned for 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The firm configuration was finalized on July 1, 2010.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By October 2011, deliveries were scheduled to begin in 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The prototype 787-9 made its maiden flight from Paine Field on September 17, 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By November 8, 2013, it had flown 141 hours.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A 787-9 was on static display at the 2014 Farnborough Air Show prior to first delivery.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On July 8, 2014, launch customer Air New Zealand took its first 787-9, in a distinctive black livery in a ceremony at Paine Field.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first revenue service was operated by All Nippon Airways on August 7, 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Air New Zealand operated its first commercial flight from Auckland to Sydney on August 9, 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-9 was to begin commercial service with All Nippon Airways on August 7, 2014.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] United Airlines was to start the longest nonstop scheduled 787 service between Los Angeles and Melbourne in October 2014, and the longest California-Australia route in 2026, being San Francisco to Adelaide in 2025.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Air China started a 787-9 route between Beijing and Chengdu in May 2016.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of January 2023, 63% of all 787 orders are for the 787-9, with 580 deliveries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 20-foot (6.1 m) stretch was achieved by adding 10-foot (3.0 m) (five-frame) extensions forward and aft of the wing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-8 and 787-9 have 50% commonality: the wing, fuselage and systems of the 787-8 had required radical revision to achieve the payload-range goals of the 787-9.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Following a major revamp of the original 787-8 wing, the latest configuration for the 787-9 and -10 is the fourth design evolution.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On March 25, 2018, a Qantas 787-9 completed the first scheduled non-stop flight between Australia and the UK flying seventeen hours from Perth to London Heathrow.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On October 20, 2019, a Qantas 787-9 was flight tested from New York to Sydney with a restricted payload.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A team of researchers monitored passengers and crew to investigate wellness and performance on long flights.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In December 2005, pushed by the interest of Emirates and Qantas, Boeing was studying the possibility of stretching the 787-9 further to seat 290 to 310 passengers.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This variant would be similar to the capacity of the Boeing 777-200 and the Airbus A350-900, although with a shorter range.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Customer discussions were continuing in early 2006.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Mike Bair, Boeing's vice president and general manager for the 787 development program at the time, said it was easier to proceed with the 787-10 development after other customers followed Emirates' request.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This variant is targeted to replace the Boeing 767-400ER and Airbus A330-300.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On May 30, 2013, Singapore Airlines became the launch customer by stating it would order 30 787-10s (provided Boeing launched the program), to be delivered in 2018–2019.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On June 18, 2013, Boeing officially launched the 787-10 at the Paris Air Show, with orders or commitments for 102 aircraft from Air Lease Corporation (30), Singapore Airlines (30), United Airlines (20), British Airways (12), and GE Capital Aviation Services (10).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of January 2023, the aircraft has 189 orders out of which 115 have been delivered, 7 of which are stored.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This variant was envisioned as replacing Boeing 777-200 and Airbus A340-500 aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It competes with the Airbus A350-900, and according to Boeing, it offers better economics than its Airbus competitor on shorter routes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Steven Udvar-Hazy said, "If it's identically configured, the -10 has a little bit of an edge on the -900", but smaller than Boeing's estimate of 10 percent.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-10 is 224 ft (68 m) long, seats 336 passengers in a two-class cabin configuration, and has a range of 6,330 nmi (11,720 km; 7,280 mi).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing completed detailed design for the -10 on December 2, 2015.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Designers targeted 90% commonality between the 787-9 and -10 and achieved 95%; the 18-foot (5.5 m) stretch was reached by adding 10 ft (3 m) forward of the wing and 8 ft (2.4 m) aft, and by strengthening the fuselage for bending loads in the center wingbox.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Because of the length and additional tail strike protection needed, a semilevered landing gear enables rotation over the aft wheels rather than at the bogie center, like the 777-300ER, and the cabin air conditioning system has 15% more capacity.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first and third -10 test-platforms incorporate Rolls-Royce's new Trent 1000 TEN engines, while the second is powered by the competing General Electric GEnx-1B engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Major fuselage parts were received for final assembly on November 30, 2016.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 787-10's mid-fuselage sections are too large for transport to Everett, Washington and it is built only in Charleston, South Carolina; it is the first Boeing airliner assembled exclusively there.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first -10 was rolled out on February 17, 2017.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The variant's first flight took place on March 31, 2017, and lasted 4 hours and 48 minutes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first test 787-10 aircraft is engaged in flight envelope expansion work and the second joined the program in early May 2017, while the third with a passenger cabin interior to test the uprated environmental control system and Trent fuel-burn performance was scheduled to join in June.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The -10 was scheduled to appear at the 2017 Paris Air Show.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The second -10 is being used to prove the GE Aviation engines and the third made its first flight on June 8, 2017, when the flight-test programme was 30% complete.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing finished final assembly and painting of the first production 787-10 in October 2017, before its certification.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The last stages of flight tests focused on fuel burn validation and revised flight control software.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] At the start of the November 2017 Dubai Air Show, the 787-10 had 171 orders; Emirates committed to 40 787-10s, in two- and three-class cabins for 240 to 330 passengers, to be delivered from 2022 and with conversion rights to the smaller 787-9.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] These aircraft are adapted for 7–8.5 hour missions, in a 280-seat three–class layout.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Emirates' Tim Clark was doubtful it would meet its MTOW for the payload-range required with initial 70,000–72,000 lbf (310–320 kN) thrust engines, but with the current 76,000 lbf (340 kN) turbofans and the -9 early margins gave the -10 "stellar economics".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By early 2019, Emirates was considering canceling its 787-10 order, due to engine margins being insufficient for the hot Dubai weather, in favor of the Airbus A350 (which would also replace its last Airbus A380 order).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] At the 2019 Dubai Air Show, Emirates placed an order for 30 787-9 aircraft rather than the 787-10.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In January 2018, the -10 was certified by the FAA after testing for 900 flight hours.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing received its production certificate on February 15.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It was first delivered to launch customer Singapore Airlines on March 25, 2018.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Fitted with 337 seats, 36 in business and 301 in economy, the -10 began commercial service on April 3, 2018.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 8.7% fuselage stretch from the -9 to the -10 likely increased empty weight at a lower rate than the 7.4% growth from the -8 to the -9 due to the 10.7% stretch.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Software changes increased the tailplane effectiveness to avoid modifying it.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] To replace Air New Zealand's 777-200 fleet, Boeing wants to increase the 787-10 MTOW by over 13,000 pounds (5.9 t) to 572,000 pounds (259 t) with some reinforcements and updated fuel systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This would allow more range, such as the 5,600 nmi (10,400 km; 6,400 mi) trip from Auckland to Los Angeles with no passenger restrictions and some cargo.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The increased performance could trickle down to the 787-9, allowing Auckland to New York flights.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Through June 2018, fifteen have been ordered, twelve delivered and four were in service.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Two 787 aircraft have been used in Boeing's ecoDemonstrator program which aims to develop technology and techniques to reduce the environmental effects of aviation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The testing involves many partner organizations including engine and systems manufacturers, NASA, academic, research, and regulatory institutions.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The program started in 2011 with a different airframe being used each year.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2014, the fourth prototype 787-8 was used for tests including use of sustainable aviation fuel, ceramic matrix composite engine exhaust nozzles, and systems for improved air traffic control (ATC) communications and closer landing approach spacing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In 2020, a new 787-10 took part in the program, including intensive noise reduction trials, and including text-based ATC communications and cabin hygiene and cleansing tests related to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] After removal of the test equipment, the aircraft was delivered to Etihad Airways.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In April 2023, Boeing announced the ecoDemonstrator Explorer program, which would run alongside the ecoDemonstrator program.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first Explorer program in 2023 tested international route planning (trajectory-based operations – a major aim of the FAA's NextGen project) and maximization of sustainable aviation fuel use for a planned 10% fuel efficiency gain, using a 787-10.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] There are 1,006 Boeing 787 aircraft in airline service as of February 2022, comprising 377 Boeing 787-8s, 568 787-9s and 61 787-10s, with outstanding orders for further 481 aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of August 2019, the largest operators are All Nippon Airways (77), United Airlines (63), Japan Airlines (47), and American Airlines (46).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In September 2011, the 787 was first officially delivered to launch customer All Nippon Airways.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On December 13, 2018, the 787th Boeing 787 was delivered to AerCap and leased to China Southern Airlines.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By then the 787 had flown 300 million passengers on 1.5 million flights and opened 210 new nonstop routes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The 1000th Dreamliner, a 787-10 for Singapore Airlines, made its maiden flight on April 3, 2020.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Boeing 787 has been involved in eight accidents and incidents as of June 2025, including one hull loss, which was also the only accident involving fatalities.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On June 12, 2025, Air India Flight 171, an 11-year-old Boeing 787-8 registered as VT-ANB operating from Ahmedabad Airport to London Gatwick Airport, crashed into the hostel building of B.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] According to the preliminary Aircraft Accident Investigation Bureau report released on July 8, 2025, the crash was caused by both engines shutting down after their fuel control switches moved from the "RUN" to "CUTOFF" position.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The cause of the switch movement remains under investigation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The report did not recommend any actions to Boeing, or 787 operators.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] All but one of the 242 people on board were killed, as well as 19 people on the ground.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The sole survivor was a British national seated in 11A, next to an emergency exit.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This marked the first fatal crash and hull loss of a 787.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A Japan Airlines (JAL) 787 experienced a fuel leak on January 8, 2013, and its flight from Boston was canceled.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The next day, United Airlines reported a problem in one of its six 787s with the wiring near the main batteries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Soon, the US National Transportation Safety Board opened a safety probe.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Fuel leaks also occurred on January 11, 2013 and on January 13, 2013, at Narita International Airport outside Tokyo.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The aircraft reportedly was the same one that had a fuel leak on January 8.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Japan's transport ministry also launched an investigation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 11, 2013, the FAA completed a comprehensive review of the 787's critical systems including the design, manufacture, and assembly.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Department of Transportation secretary Ray LaHood stated the administration was "looking for the root causes" behind the recent issues.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On July 12, 2013, a fire started on an empty Ethiopian Airlines 787 parked at Heathrow Airport before it was extinguished by the airport fire and rescue service.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The fire caused extensive heat damage to the aircraft.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The FAA and NTSB sent representatives to assist in the investigation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The initial investigation found no direct link with the aircraft's main batteries.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Further investigations indicated that the fire was due to lithium-manganese dioxide batteries powering an emergency locator transmitter (ELT).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The UK Air Accidents Investigation Branch (AAIB) issued a special bulletin on July 18, 2013, requesting the US FAA ensure that the locator is removed or disconnected in Boeing 787s and to review the safety of lithium battery-powered ELT systems in other aircraft types.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On August 19, 2015, the Associated Press reported that the fire was started by a short circuit caused by crossed wires located under the battery.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On July 26, 2013, ANA said it had found wiring damage on two 787 locator beacons.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] United Airlines also reported that it had found a pinched wire in one 787 locator beacon.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On August 14, 2013, the media reported a fire extinguisher fault affecting three ANA airplanes, which caused the fire extinguishers to discharge into the opposite engine from the one requested.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The fault was caused by a supplier assembly error.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On November 22, 2013, Boeing issued an advisory to airlines using General Electric GEnx engines on 787 and 747-8 aircraft to avoid flying near high-level thunderstorms due to an increased risk of icing on the engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The problem was caused by a buildup of ice crystals just behind the main fan causing a brief loss of thrust on six occasions.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 21, 2014, a Norwegian Air Shuttle 787 experienced a fuel leak which caused a 19-hour delay to a flight from Bangkok to Oslo.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The leak became known to pilots only after it was pointed out by concerned passengers.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It was found later that a faulty valve was responsible.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This fuel leak is one of numerous problems experienced by Norwegian Air Shuttle's 787 fleet.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On April 22, 2016, the FAA issued an airworthiness directive following a January 29, 2016 incident in which a General Electric GEnx-1B PIP2 engine suffered damage and non-restartable power loss while flying at an altitude of 20,000 feet.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The damage is thought to have been caused by a fan imbalance resulting from fan ice shedding.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On March 11, 2024, LATAM Airlines Flight 800 experienced a sudden drop in altitude, resulting in 50 injuries to those aboard and 12 with serious injuries being hospitalized.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The final report On 22 February 2026, concluded that the captain exerted pressure on the control column sensor due to his accidental seat movement, which overrode the autopilot causing a temporary loss of control.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 24, 2025, United Airlines Flight 613, a Boeing 787‑8 registered N27903, operating from Lagos, Nigeria to Washington Dulles, US, experienced a sudden and unexpected altitude drop over Ivory Coast airspace.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The autopilot disengaged following the failure of both inertial reference units (IRUs), prompting a rapid descent that injured 38 individuals (including four passengers and two crew members seriously).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The US National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) launched a joint investigation with Nigerian authorities.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A preliminary report released in March 2025 confirmed the IRU malfunction as the likely cause.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 16, 2013, All Nippon Airways Flight 692, en route from Yamaguchi Ube Airport to Tokyo Haneda, had a battery problem warning followed by a burning smell while climbing from Ube about 35 nautical miles (65 km; 40 mi) west of Takamatsu, Japan.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The aircraft diverted to Takamatsu and was evacuated via the slides; three passengers received minor injuries during the evacuation.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A similar incident in a parked Japan Airlines 787 at Boston's Logan International Airport within the same week led the Federal Aviation Administration to ground all 787s.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 16, 2013, both major Japanese airlines ANA and JAL voluntarily grounded their fleets of 787s after multiple incidents involving different 787s, including emergency landings.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] At the time, these two carriers operated 24 of the 50 787s delivered.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The grounding reportedly cost ANA some 9 billion yen (US$93 million) in lost sales.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 16, 2013, the FAA issued an emergency airworthiness directive ordering all American-based airlines to ground their Boeing 787s until yet-to-be-determined modifications were made to the electrical system to reduce the risk of the battery overheating or catching fire.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] This was the first time that the FAA had grounded an airliner type since 1979.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Industry experts disagreed on consequences of the grounding: Airbus was confident that Boeing would resolve the issue and that no airlines will switch plane type, while other experts saw the problem as "costly" and "could take upwards of a year".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The FAA also conducted an extensive review of the 787's critical systems.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The focus of the review was on the safety of the lithium-ion batteries made of lithium cobalt oxide (LiCoO2).
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] FAA approved a 787 battery in 2007 with nine "special conditions".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] A battery approved by FAA (through Mobile Power Solutions) was made by Rose Electronics using Kokam cells; the batteries installed in the 787 are made by Yuasa.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The first big hurdle for Boeing was that the ranks of commercial aircraft engineers lacked lithium-ion battery expertise in that lithium-ion batteries had never before been used on a Boeing commercial jet.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing chief technology officer John Tracy began canvassing the entire organization for lithium-ion battery experts.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] He also began calling his contacts outside the aerospace industry.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Within a day, about a dozen Boeing engineers from across the United States assembled at Boeing's Everett, Washington engineering center.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The collaborators began ongoing collaborative group sessions—not just a series of meetings—that lasted weeks with breaks only for meals and sleep.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Evan Rosen writes in *The Culture of Collaboration* (2024, expanded and updated edition) that for the Boeing 787 battery effort, hierarchy was out the window, because the collaborators were working outside of their usual reporting structure.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Hidden agendas and internal competition were gone, because everybody had the same goal, Rosen writes.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 20, the NTSB declared that overvoltage was not the cause of the Boston incident, as voltage did not exceed the battery limit of 32 V, and the charging unit passed tests.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The battery had signs of short circuiting and thermal runaway.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Despite this, by January 24, the NTSB had not yet pinpointed the cause of the Boston fire; the FAA would not allow US-based 787s to fly again until the problem was found and corrected.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In a press briefing that day, NTSB Chairwoman Deborah Hersman said that the NTSB had found evidence of failure of multiple safety systems designed to prevent these battery problems, and stated that fire must never happen on an airplane.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Japan Transport Safety Board (JTSB) said on January 23 that the battery in ANA jets in Japan reached a maximum voltage of 31 V (below the 32 V limit like the Boston JAL 787), but had a sudden unexplained voltage drop to near zero.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] All cells had signs of thermal damage prior to runaway.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] ANA and JAL had replaced several 787 batteries before the mishaps.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] As of January 29, 2013, JTSB approved the Yuasa factory quality control while the NTSB examined the Boston battery for defects.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The failure rate, with two major battery thermal runaway events in 100,000 flight hours, was much higher than the rate of one in 10 million flight hours predicted by Boeing.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The only American airline that operated the Dreamliner at the time was United Airlines, which had six.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Chile's Directorate General of Civil Aviation (DGAC) grounded LAN Airlines' three 787s.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Indian Directorate General of Civil Aviation (DGCA) directed Air India to ground its six Dreamliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The Japanese Transport Ministry made the ANA and JAL groundings official and indefinite following the FAA announcement.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The European Aviation Safety Agency also followed the FAA's advice and grounded the only two European 787s operated by LOT Polish Airlines.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Qatar Airways grounded their five Dreamliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Ethiopian Airlines was the final operator to temporarily ground its four Dreamliners.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] By January 17, 2013, all 50 of the aircraft delivered to date had been grounded.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 18, Boeing halted 787 deliveries until the battery problem was resolved.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On February 7, 2013, the FAA gave approval for Boeing to conduct 787 test flights to gather additional data.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] In February 2013, FAA oversight of the 787's 2007 safety approval and certification was under scrutiny.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On March 7, 2013, the NTSB released an interim factual report about the Boston battery fire on January 7, 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The investigation stated that "heavy smoke and fire coming from the front of the APU battery case." Firefighters "tried fire extinguishing, but smoke and flame (flame size about 3 inches, or 8 cm) did not stop".
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Boeing completed its final tests on a revised battery design on April 5, 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The FAA approved Boeing's revised battery design with three additional, overlapping protection methods on April 19, 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The FAA published a directive on April 25 to provide instructions for retrofitting battery hardware before the 787s could return to flight.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The repairs were expected to be completed in weeks.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] Following the FAA approval in the U.S. effective April 26, Japan approved resumption of Boeing 787 flights in the country on April 26, 2013.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On April 27, 2013, Ethiopian Airlines took a 787 on the model's first commercial flight after battery system modifications.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] On January 14, 2014, a battery in a JAL 787 emitted smoke from the battery's protection exhaust while the aircraft was undergoing pre-flight maintenance at Tokyo Narita Airport.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The battery partially melted in the incident; one of its eight lithium-ion cells had its relief port vent and fluid sprayed inside the battery's container.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It was later reported that the battery may have reached a temperature as high as 1,220 °F (660 °C), and that Boeing did not understand the root cause of the failure.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The NTSB criticized the FAA, Boeing, and battery manufacturers for the faults in a 2014 report.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] It also criticized the GE-made flight data and cockpit voice recorder in the same report.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p02] The enclosure Boeing added is 185 lb (84 kg) heavier, negating the lighter battery potential.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p03] All three prototype 787-8s are preserved in museums.
[src:jet-propulsion/boeing-787-dreamliner-p03] At maximum takeoff weight, International Standard Atmosphere, sea-level, hi thrust.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The **Brayton cycle**, also known as the **Joule cycle**, is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the operation of certain heat engines that have air or some other gas as their working fluid.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] It is characterized by isentropic compression and expansion, and isobaric heat addition and rejection, though practical engines have adiabatic rather than isentropic steps.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The most common current application is in airbreathing jet engines and gas turbine engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The engine cycle is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer, who developed the Brayton Ready Motor in 1872, using a piston compressor and piston expander.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] An engine using the cycle was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791, using a reciprocating compressor and a turbine expander.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] There are two main types of Brayton cycles: closed and open.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In a closed cycle, the working gas stays inside the engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Heat is introduced with a heat exchanger or external combustion and expelled with a heat exchanger.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] With the open cycle, air from the atmosphere is drawn in, goes through three steps of the cycle, and is expelled again to the atmosphere.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Open cycles allow for internal combustion.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Although the cycle is open, it is conventionally assumed for the purposes of thermodynamic analysis that the exhaust gases are reused in the intake, enabling analysis as a closed cycle.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1872, George Brayton applied for a patent for his "Ready Motor", a reciprocating heat engine operating on a gas power cycle.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The engine was a two-stroke and produced power on every revolution.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Brayton engines used a separate piston compressor and piston expander, with compressed air heated by internal fire as it entered the expander cylinder.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The first versions of the Brayton engine were vapor engines which mixed fuel with air as it entered the compressor; town gas was used or a surface carburetor was also used for mobile operation .
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The fuel / air was contained in a reservoir / tank and then it was admitted to the expansion cylinder and burned.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] As the fuel/air mixture entered the expansion cylinder, it was ignited by a pilot flame.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] A screen was used to prevent the fire from entering or returning to the reservoir.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In early versions of the engine, this screen sometimes failed and an explosion would occur.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1874, Brayton solved the explosion problem by adding the fuel just prior to the expander cylinder.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The engine now used heavier fuels such as kerosene and fuel oil.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Brayton produced and sold "Ready Motors" to perform a variety of tasks like water pumping, mill operation, running generators, and marine propulsion.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The "Ready Motors" were produced from 1872 to sometime in the 1880s; several hundred such motors were likely produced during this time period.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Brayton licensed the design to Simone in the UK.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Many variations of the layout were used; some were single-acting and some were double-acting.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Some had under walking beams; others had overhead walking beams.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Both horizontal and vertical models were built.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Sizes ranged from less than one to over 40 horsepower.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Critics of the time claimed the engines ran smoothly and had a reasonable efficiency.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Brayton-cycle engines were some of the first internal combustion engines used for motive power.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1875, John Holland used a Brayton engine to power the world's first self-propelled submarine (Holland boat #1).
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1879, a Brayton engine was used to power a second submarine, the *Fenian Ram*.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] John Philip Holland's submarines are preserved in the Paterson Museum in the Old Great Falls Historic District of Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Selden patented the first internal combustion automobile.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Inspired by the internal combustion engine invented by Brayton displayed at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, Selden patented a four-wheel car working on a smaller, lighter, multicylinder version.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] He then filed a series of amendments to his application which stretched out the legal process, resulting in a delay of 16 years before the patent was granted on November 5, 1895.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1903, Selden sued Ford for patent infringement and Henry Ford fought the Selden patent until 1911.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Selden had never actually produced a working car, so during the trial, two machines were constructed according to the patent drawings.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Ford argued his cars used the four-stroke Alphonse Beau de Rochas cycle or Otto cycle and not the Brayton-cycle engine used in the Selden auto.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Ford won the appeal of the original case.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1887, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke direct-injection oil engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The fuel system used a variable-quantity pump and liquid-fuel, high-pressure, spray-type injection.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The liquid was forced through a spring-loaded, relief-type valve (injector) which caused the fuel to become divided into small droplets.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Injection was timed to occur at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] A platinum igniter provided the source of ignition.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In this manner, the engine fired on every power stroke and speed and output were controlled solely by the quantity of fuel injected.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In 1890, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke, air-blast oil engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The fuel system delivered a variable quantity of vaporized fuel to the center of the cylinder under pressure at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] The ignition source was an igniter made from platinum wire.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] A variable-quantity injection pump provided the fuel to an injector where it was mixed with air as it entered the cylinder.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] A small crank-driven compressor provided the source for air.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] This engine also used the lean-burn system.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Rudolf Diesel originally proposed a very high compression, constant-temperature cycle where the heat of compression would exceed the heat of combustion, but after several years of experiments, he realized that the constant-temperature cycle would not work in a piston engine.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Early Diesel engines use an air blast system which was pioneered by Brayton in 1890.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Consequently, these early engines use the constant-pressure cycle.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] A Brayton-type engine consists of three components: a compressor, a mixing chamber, and an expander.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] Modern Brayton engines are almost always a turbine type, although Brayton only made piston engines.
[src:jet-propulsion/brayton-cycle] In the original 19th-century Brayton engine, ambient air is drawn into a piston compressor, where it is compressed; ideally an isentropic process.
